dev/plans/runs/G3_5-cache-pressure-telemetry-20260504T144523Z.log:58:{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_013SanTD3wDu1VkTmhX3cxAU","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# Pack 6.G handoff — Canonical-SQLite tuning on the F.0 baseline\n2\t\n3\tPhase 9 Pack 6.G continues AC-020 closure work after Pack 6 closed\n4\tF.0 (thread-affine reader workers KEPT, human override of REVERT\n5\trule) on 2026-05-04. Pack 6.G stays inside canonical/release SQLite\n6\t— no WAL2, no `libsqlite3-sys` swap, no rusqlite replacement. Those\n7\tremain Pack 7+ research territory.\n8\t\n9\tF.0 removed Rust-side ReaderPool / cross-thread-handoff cost\n10\t(speedup 1.49×→3.49×, +2.34×). The residual gap is now plausibly\n11\tSQLite-internal: WAL shared-memory atomics, checkpoint pressure,\n12\tper-connection allocator (lookaside), and / or parse cost on\n13\tsticky long-lived reader connections. Pack 6.G attacks each of\n14\tthose with the smallest-radius, highest-evidence canonical-SQLite\n15\tlevers, in the order the telemetry pass picks.\n16\t\n17\t## 1. Read order on resume\n18\t\n19\t1. `dev/plan/runs/STATUS.md` — Pack 6 closed state + Pack 6.G\n20\t   active phase.\n21\t2. `dev/plan/runs/F0-thread-affine-readers-output.json` — F.0\n22\t   numeric baseline + worker pool topology summary.\n23\t3. `dev/plan/runs/F0-review-20260504T122055Z.md` — codex BLOCK\n24\t   findings + override rationale; key for future spawn discipline.\n25\t4. `dev/notes/performance-whitepaper-notes.md` §4 (kept) + §5\n26\t   (do-not-retry) + §11 (Pack 5 narrative). §5 still binds — no\n27\t   retry of B.1 / C.1 / E.1 without explicit override.\n28\t5. `dev/plan/prompts/01-orchestrator-resume.md` §4 — anti-chaining\n29\t   defenses (PREAMBLE + `--disallowedTools Task Agent` + stream-\n30\t   json). Apply on every spawn.\n31\t6. The next phase prompt per \"Next action\" in STATUS.md.\n32\t\n33\t## 2. State at this hand-off\n34\t\n35\t- Branch: `0.6.0-rewrite`. Tip: `a00cd13` at handoff creation.\n36\t- F.0 commits already on tip: `4ebdd68` (refactor) + `29cdc6f`\n37\t  (cfg-gate fix) + `a00cd13` (KEEP bookkeeping).\n38\t- AC-020 N=5 numbers (post-F.0, this host): seq 531 ms / conc\n39\t  155 ms / speedup 3.49×. Required ≥ 5.0× KEEP / ≤ 80 ms conc.\n40\t  Gap: 75 ms above conc bound; 1.51× below speedup floor.\n41\t- Host caveat: this worktree machine runs ~3× slower in absolute\n42\t  ms than the Pack 5 reference machine. Cross-pack comparisons\n43\t  use the speedup ratio, not absolute ms.\n44\t- AC-017, AC-018 green; AC-018 drain 56 ms.\n45\t- Active worktrees: none.\n46\t- Anti-chaining defenses verified WORKING on F.0 spawn (single\n47\t  coherent agent; no Task spawns). Keep on for all G-phase spawns.\n48\t\n49\t## 3. Pack 5 / Pack 6 falsifications you do not retry\n50\t\n51\tPer the whitepaper §5 do-not-retry list:\n52\t\n53\t- Runtime `sqlite3_config(SQLITE_CONFIG_MULTITHREAD)` (B.1).\n54\t- Compile-time `SQLITE_THREADSAFE=2` rebuild (C.1).\n55\t- Read-path `prepare_cached` on borrow/release pool connections\n56\t  (E.1). **Note:** G.2 in this packet revisits `prepare_cached` on\n57\t  the F.0 _thread-affine_ connections, which is a different\n58\t  topology and a different argument. Treat G.2 as new territory,\n59\t  not an §5 retry — see G.2 prompt for the explicit override\n60\t  rationale.\n61\t- Reader `cache_size` / `mmap_size` global tuning (Pack 5 reverted\n62\t  experiment ledger). G.0 may _measure_ mmap_size effects but does\n63\t  not change the production default.\n64\t- Reader open flags `READ_ONLY | NO_MUTEX`. G-phase keeps\n65\t  serialized open flags; thread-affine ownership is the safety\n66\t  argument, not the open-flag bits.\n67\t\n68\t## 4. Authorized G-phase interventions (in execution order)\n69\t\n70\t### G.0 — WAL / checkpoint telemetry pass (read-only)\n71\t\n72\tRe-capture AC-020 perf evidence on the F.0 tip with extended\n73\tsymbol grouping. Distinguish:\n74\t\n75\t- WAL shared-memory atomics (`walIndexMap`, `walFrames`, `walRead*`\n76\t  function family, atomic / CAS primitives inside `pager.c` / `wal.c`).\n77\t- Checkpoint cost (`sqlite3WalCheckpoint`, busy-handler interaction,\n78\t  auto-checkpoint threshold hits).\n79\t- Per-connection allocator behavior (`sqlite3MallocSize`,\n80\t  `sqlite3_release_memory`, lookaside hit/miss if surfaceable).\n81\t- Parse cost on sticky reader connections (`sqlite3RunParser`,\n82\t  `sqlite3VdbePrepare`). Should be high if E.1 hypothesis applies\n83\t  to F.0 topology; should be low if F.0 already amortized it.\n84\t- Our code share (engine + worker dispatch).\n85\t\n86\tOutput: classification JSON + a short reviewer-ready note picking\n87\tthe strongest single lever among G.1 / G.2 / G.3 for the next\n88\tphase. No production code change. No commit unless the diagnostic\n89\tadds a `#[ignore]`-gated counter test.\n90\t\n91\t### G.1 — Reader-worker lookaside tuning\n92\t\n93\tConfigure SQLite per-connection lookaside immediately after\n94\t`Connection::open` for each F.0 reader worker. Use\n95\t`sqlite3_db_config(SQLITE_DBCONFIG_LOOKASIDE, ...)` with\n96\tdocumented sane defaults (per <https://www.sqlite.org/malloc.html>\n97\t§3 — typical 1200-byte slots, 100 slots, sized for the workload's\n98\tprepared-statement footprint; revise from G.0 evidence).\n99\t\n100\tExpected impact (per SQLite docs): ~10–15% overall perf in\n101\tallocator-heavy workloads. Reader-side, expressed across N=8\n102\tworkers with sticky connections, is exactly the documented happy\n103\tpath. Sequential effect: small. Concurrent effect: small-to-\n104\tmedium if the allocator is contended.\n105\t\n106\tKEEP / REVERT decision rule lives in `G1-reader-lookaside.md`.\n107\tNumeric KEEP target: any clean, reproducible improvement on\n108\tconcurrent_median_ms with no AC-017 / AC-018 regression. Lookaside\n109\tis too small a lever to require AC-020 closure alone — it is a\n110\tsequencing decision, not a closer.\n111\t\n112\t### G.2 — Per-worker prepared-statement cache (sticky-connection revisit of E.1)\n113\t\n114\tE.1 (Pack 5) added `prepare_cached` on the four read-path search\n115\tstatements against borrow/release pool connections. Sequential\n116\timproved -13.7%, concurrent unchanged, ratio worsened, codex BLOCK\n117\ton public surface + decision-rule mismatch + partial test. REVERTED.\n118\t\n119\tThe F.0 topology _is_ the natural shape for prepared-statement\n120\tcaching: each reader worker owns one connection for its lifetime,\n121\tso the cache amortizes across the worker's full lifetime, not just\n122\tthe brief borrow window. G.2 re-runs that experiment with two\n123\tbinding constraints from E.1's review:\n124\t\n125\t- All four statements covered (no partial test).\n126\t- No public Rust API expansion. Use private worker-internal cache\n127\t  with an integration test that drives observable behavior, not a\n128\t  `pub fn ..._for_test` accessor unless it is `#[cfg(debug_assertions)]`-gated and explicitly justified in the diff.\n129\t\n130\tKEEP target: AC-020 numerics improve cleanly (no ratio worsening).\n131\tThe Pack 5 §5 entry binds: G.2 is not a retry of the same\n132\texperiment; it is the same SQL change applied to a strictly\n133\tdifferent connection-lifetime topology. Whitepaper §12 carries the\n134\texplicit override note.\n135\t\n136\t### G.3 — WAL checkpoint policy / tuning\n137\t\n138\tAdjust auto-checkpoint threshold (PRAGMA `wal_autocheckpoint`),\n139\tbusy timeout, or move to an explicit application-driven checkpoint\n140\tschedule on the writer side. If G.0 telemetry says checkpoint cost\n141\tis small or zero on the read-heavy fixture, G.3 may be SKIPPED in\n142\tthis packet and queued for a real-write-load packet.\n143\t\n144\tKEEP target: lower variance + lower max latency on AC-020\n145\tconcurrent runs without regressing AC-017 / AC-018.\n146\t\n147\t## 5. Phase ordering\n148\t\n149\t1. G.0 telemetry first. Picks strongest lever or surfaces a non-\n150\t   listed bottleneck (orchestrator pivot point).\n151\t2. Run interventions in the order G.0 picks. Default order is\n152\t   G.1 → G.2 → G.3.\n153\t3. After each intervention: KEEP or REVERT, then re-measure\n154\t   AC-020 N=5 and update the chained baseline-of-record.\n155\t4. Final synthesis at packet close: cumulative speedup vs F.0\n156\t   baseline (3.49×) and vs the original Pack 5 baseline (1.49×).\n157\t\n158\t## 6. Decision rules (per phase)\n159\t\n160\t- KEEP iff AC-017 + AC-018 stay green AND AC-020 numerics improve\n161\t  cleanly (no ratio worsening, no concurrent_median_ms regression\n162\t  outside one stddev) AND no contract / public-surface violation.\n163\t- INCONCLUSIVE iff numerics flat within noise; record evidence and\n164\t  move on.\n165\t- REVERT iff any of the above fails.\n166\t\n167\tThe packet-close success definition is **not** \"AC-020 closes\n168\twithin 0.6.0\". It is \"every canonical-SQLite lever has been tried,\n169\tKEEPs are landed, and the residual gap is documented well enough\n170\tthat Pack 7 (WAL2 / vendor-SQLite / reader-writer split) can be\n171\tscoped from evidence rather than guess.\"\n172\t\n173\t## 7. Reviewer requirements\n174\t\n175\tCodex `gpt-5.4` high reviewer **mandatory on KEEP / INCONCLUSIVE**\n176\tfor G.1 / G.2 / G.3. G.0 is read-only diagnostics — reviewer\n177\toptional unless it lands a counter test.\n178\t\n179\tReviewer must confirm per phase:\n180\t\n181\t- No retry of an §5 do-not-retry experiment without explicit\n182\t  override note in the prompt + whitepaper.\n183\t- No public Rust API expansion without ADR / interface-doc work,\n184\t  or `#[cfg(debug_assertions)]` gating with the existing convention.\n185\t- AC-018 unchanged; same-snapshot cursor contract (REQ-013 /\n186\t  AC-059b / REQ-055) preserved.\n187\t- `./scripts/agent-verify.sh` run after meaningful edits (not\n188\t  `dev/agent-verify.sh` — that path does not exist, F.0 reviewer\n189\t  block #3).\n190\t\n191\t## 8. Out of scope for Pack 6.G\n192\t\n193\t- WAL2 mode. Branch-only SQLite; Pack 7 territory.\n194\t- `libsqlite3-sys` replacement / vendor-SQLite path. Pack 7.\n195\t- Reader/writer physical separation. Pack 7.\n196\t- Schema/index changes (e.g. `canonical_nodes(write_cursor)`).\n197\t- Any change that re-opens borrow/release pooling. F.0 is the\n198\t  load-bearing topology for the entire G-phase.\n199\t- Public Rust API expansion. `_for_test` accessors only with\n200\t  `#[cfg(debug_assertions)]` per F.0 reviewer convention.\n201\t\n202\t## 9. Failure interpretation\n203\t\n204\tIf G.0 + G.1 + G.2 + G.3 all land KEEP and AC-020 still does not\n205\tclose: ship 0.6.0 with REQ-020 deferred (per the F.0 packet-close\n206\tposition) and open Pack 7 with the cumulative G-phase evidence as\n207\tthe input.\n208\t\n209\tIf telemetry instead surfaces a **new** bottleneck class (e.g. a\n210\tspecific hot path in `vec0` that is amenable to a SQL or query-\n211\tplan tweak), the orchestrator may add a G.4 phase by appending to\n212\tthis handoff and the STATUS phase-results table — same review +\n213\tTDD discipline applies.\n214\t\n215\t## 10. Spawning interventions\n216\t\n217\tUse the resume §4 spawn block with anti-chaining defenses. Per-\n218\tphase prompts live alongside this handoff:\n219\t\n220\t- `dev/plan/prompts/G0-wal-checkpoint-telemetry.md`\n221\t- `dev/plan/prompts/G1-reader-lookaside.md` (authored after G.0)\n222\t- `dev/plan/prompts/G2-per-worker-stmt-cache.md` (authored after\n223\t  G.0 / G.1 KEEP)\n224\t- `dev/plan/prompts/G3-checkpoint-tuning.md` (authored after\n225\t  G.0 / G.1 / G.2)\n226\t\n227\tImplementer model: Opus 4.7 high. Reviewer: codex `gpt-5.4` high.\n228\tWorktree pattern: `/tmp/fdb-pack6G-<phase>-<ts>`. Branch:\n229\t`pack6G-<phase>-<ts>`.\n230\t\n231\t## 11. Pause points\n232\t\n233\t- After G.0 returns. Orchestrator reviews telemetry JSON, picks\n234\t  next-phase ordering, and pauses for human review before\n235\t  spawning G.1.\n236\t- After each KEEP / REVERT decision (§3 update protocol in\n237\t  `01-orchestrator-resume.md`).\n238\t- After packet close (cumulative-vs-F.0 + cumulative-vs-Pack-5\n239\t  numbers in the final synthesis JSON).\n240\t\n241\t## Update log\n242\t\n243\t- 2026-05-04 — Authored from the user's \"Best next opportunities\n244\t  on top of F.0\" briefing. G.0 telemetry first; default ordering\n245\t  G.1 → G.2 → G.3; Pack 6 F.0 baseline `a00cd13` (seq 531 ms /\n246\t  conc 155 ms / speedup 3.49× / N=5).\n247\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"485c34a8-dceb-42a9-9d76-fb4335ae2dfc","uuid":"883e50f2-b7ff-4ecb-9225-8995e29d0178","timestamp":"2026-05-04T14:45:49.836Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/tmp/fdb-pack6G-G3_5-20260504T144523Z/dev/plan/prompts/04-pack6G-handoff-canonical-sqlite-tuning.md","content":"# Pack 6.G handoff — Canonical-SQLite tuning on the F.0 baseline\n\nPhase 9 Pack 6.G continues AC-020 closure work after Pack 6 closed\nF.0 (thread-affine reader workers KEPT, human override of REVERT\nrule) on 2026-05-04. Pack 6.G stays inside canonical/release SQLite\n— no WAL2, no `libsqlite3-sys` swap, no rusqlite replacement. Those\nremain Pack 7+ research territory.\n\nF.0 removed Rust-side ReaderPool / cross-thread-handoff cost\n(speedup 1.49×→3.49×, +2.34×). The residual gap is now plausibly\nSQLite-internal: WAL shared-memory atomics, checkpoint pressure,\nper-connection allocator (lookaside), and / or parse cost on\nsticky long-lived reader connections. Pack 6.G attacks each of\nthose with the smallest-radius, highest-evidence canonical-SQLite\nlevers, in the order the telemetry pass picks.\n\n## 1. Read order on resume\n\n1. `dev/plan/runs/STATUS.md` — Pack 6 closed state + Pack 6.G\n   active phase.\n2. `dev/plan/runs/F0-thread-affine-readers-output.json` — F.0\n   numeric baseline + worker pool topology summary.\n3. `dev/plan/runs/F0-review-20260504T122055Z.md` — codex BLOCK\n   findings + override rationale; key for future spawn discipline.\n4. `dev/notes/performance-whitepaper-notes.md` §4 (kept) + §5\n   (do-not-retry) + §11 (Pack 5 narrative). §5 still binds — no\n   retry of B.1 / C.1 / E.1 without explicit override.\n5. `dev/plan/prompts/01-orchestrator-resume.md` §4 — anti-chaining\n   defenses (PREAMBLE + `--disallowedTools Task Agent` + stream-\n   json). Apply on every spawn.\n6. The next phase prompt per \"Next action\" in STATUS.md.\n\n## 2. State at this hand-off\n\n- Branch: `0.6.0-rewrite`. Tip: `a00cd13` at handoff creation.\n- F.0 commits already on tip: `4ebdd68` (refactor) + `29cdc6f`\n  (cfg-gate fix) + `a00cd13` (KEEP bookkeeping).\n- AC-020 N=5 numbers (post-F.0, this host): seq 531 ms / conc\n  155 ms / speedup 3.49×. Required ≥ 5.0× KEEP / ≤ 80 ms conc.\n  Gap: 75 ms above conc bound; 1.51× below speedup floor.\n- Host caveat: this worktree machine runs ~3× slower in absolute\n  ms than the Pack 5 reference machine. Cross-pack comparisons\n  use the speedup ratio, not absolute ms.\n- AC-017, AC-018 green; AC-018 drain 56 ms.\n- Active worktrees: none.\n- Anti-chaining defenses verified WORKING on F.0 spawn (single\n  coherent agent; no Task spawns). Keep on for all G-phase spawns.\n\n## 3. Pack 5 / Pack 6 falsifications you do not retry\n\nPer the whitepaper §5 do-not-retry list:\n\n- Runtime `sqlite3_config(SQLITE_CONFIG_MULTITHREAD)` (B.1).\n- Compile-time `SQLITE_THREADSAFE=2` rebuild (C.1).\n- Read-path `prepare_cached` on borrow/release pool connections\n  (E.1). **Note:** G.2 in this packet revisits `prepare_cached` on\n  the F.0 _thread-affine_ connections, which is a different\n  topology and a different argument. Treat G.2 as new territory,\n  not an §5 retry — see G.2 prompt for the explicit override\n  rationale.\n- Reader `cache_size` / `mmap_size` global tuning (Pack 5 reverted\n  experiment ledger). G.0 may _measure_ mmap_size effects but does\n  not change the production default.\n- Reader open flags `READ_ONLY | NO_MUTEX`. G-phase keeps\n  serialized open flags; thread-affine ownership is the safety\n  argument, not the open-flag bits.\n\n## 4. Authorized G-phase interventions (in execution order)\n\n### G.0 — WAL / checkpoint telemetry pass (read-only)\n\nRe-capture AC-020 perf evidence on the F.0 tip with extended\nsymbol grouping. Distinguish:\n\n- WAL shared-memory atomics (`walIndexMap`, `walFrames`, `walRead*`\n  function family, atomic / CAS primitives inside `pager.c` / `wal.c`).\n- Checkpoint cost (`sqlite3WalCheckpoint`, busy-handler interaction,\n  auto-checkpoint threshold hits).\n- Per-connection allocator behavior (`sqlite3MallocSize`,\n  `sqlite3_release_memory`, lookaside hit/miss if surfaceable).\n- Parse cost on sticky reader connections (`sqlite3RunParser`,\n  `sqlite3VdbePrepare`). Should be high if E.1 hypothesis applies\n  to F.0 topology; should be low if F.0 already amortized it.\n- Our code share (engine + worker dispatch).\n\nOutput: classification JSON + a short reviewer-ready note picking\nthe strongest single lever among G.1 / G.2 / G.3 for the next\nphase. No production code change. No commit unless the diagnostic\nadds a `#[ignore]`-gated counter test.\n\n### G.1 — Reader-worker lookaside tuning\n\nConfigure SQLite per-connection lookaside immediately after\n`Connection::open` for each F.0 reader worker. Use\n`sqlite3_db_config(SQLITE_DBCONFIG_LOOKASIDE, ...)` with\ndocumented sane defaults (per <https://www.sqlite.org/malloc.html>\n§3 — typical 1200-byte slots, 100 slots, sized for the workload's\nprepared-statement footprint; revise from G.0 evidence).\n\nExpected impact (per SQLite docs): ~10–15% overall perf in\nallocator-heavy workloads. Reader-side, expressed across N=8\nworkers with sticky connections, is exactly the documented happy\npath. Sequential effect: small. Concurrent effect: small-to-\nmedium if the allocator is contended.\n\nKEEP / REVERT decision rule lives in `G1-reader-lookaside.md`.\nNumeric KEEP target: any clean, reproducible improvement on\nconcurrent_median_ms with no AC-017 / AC-018 regression. Lookaside\nis too small a lever to require AC-020 closure alone — it is a\nsequencing decision, not a closer.\n\n### G.2 — Per-worker prepared-statement cache (sticky-connection revisit of E.1)\n\nE.1 (Pack 5) added `prepare_cached` on the four read-path search\nstatements against borrow/release pool connections. Sequential\nimproved -13.7%, concurrent unchanged, ratio worsened, codex BLOCK\non public surface + decision-rule mismatch + partial test. REVERTED.\n\nThe F.0 topology _is_ the natural shape for prepared-statement\ncaching: each reader worker owns one connection for its lifetime,\nso the cache amortizes across the worker's full lifetime, not just\nthe brief borrow window. G.2 re-runs that experiment with two\nbinding constraints from E.1's review:\n\n- All four statements covered (no partial test).\n- No public Rust API expansion. Use private worker-internal cache\n  with an integration test that drives observable behavior, not a\n  `pub fn ..._for_test` accessor unless it is `#[cfg(debug_assertions)]`-gated and explicitly justified in the diff.\n\nKEEP target: AC-020 numerics improve cleanly (no ratio worsening).\nThe Pack 5 §5 entry binds: G.2 is not a retry of the same\nexperiment; it is the same SQL change applied to a strictly\ndifferent connection-lifetime topology. Whitepaper §12 carries the\nexplicit override note.\n\n### G.3 — WAL checkpoint policy / tuning\n\nAdjust auto-checkpoint threshold (PRAGMA `wal_autocheckpoint`),\nbusy timeout, or move to an explicit application-driven checkpoint\nschedule on the writer side. If G.0 telemetry says checkpoint cost\nis small or zero on the read-heavy fixture, G.3 may be SKIPPED in\nthis packet and queued for a real-write-load packet.\n\nKEEP target: lower variance + lower max latency on AC-020\nconcurrent runs without regressing AC-017 / AC-018.\n\n## 5. Phase ordering\n\n1. G.0 telemetry first. Picks strongest lever or surfaces a non-\n   listed bottleneck (orchestrator pivot point).\n2. Run interventions in the order G.0 picks. Default order is\n   G.1 → G.2 → G.3.\n3. After each intervention: KEEP or REVERT, then re-measure\n   AC-020 N=5 and update the chained baseline-of-record.\n4. Final synthesis at packet close: cumulative speedup vs F.0\n   baseline (3.49×) and vs the original Pack 5 baseline (1.49×).\n\n## 6. Decision rules (per phase)\n\n- KEEP iff AC-017 + AC-018 stay green AND AC-020 numerics improve\n  cleanly (no ratio worsening, no concurrent_median_ms regression\n  outside one stddev) AND no contract / public-surface violation.\n- INCONCLUSIVE iff numerics flat within noise; record evidence and\n  move on.\n- REVERT iff any of the above fails.\n\nThe packet-close success definition is **not** \"AC-020 closes\nwithin 0.6.0\". It is \"every canonical-SQLite lever has been tried,\nKEEPs are landed, and the residual gap is documented well enough\nthat Pack 7 (WAL2 / vendor-SQLite / reader-writer split) can be\nscoped from evidence rather than guess.\"\n\n## 7. Reviewer requirements\n\nCodex `gpt-5.4` high reviewer **mandatory on KEEP / INCONCLUSIVE**\nfor G.1 / G.2 / G.3. G.0 is read-only diagnostics — reviewer\noptional unless it lands a counter test.\n\nReviewer must confirm per phase:\n\n- No retry of an §5 do-not-retry experiment without explicit\n  override note in the prompt + whitepaper.\n- No public Rust API expansion without ADR / interface-doc work,\n  or `#[cfg(debug_assertions)]` gating with the existing convention.\n- AC-018 unchanged; same-snapshot cursor contract (REQ-013 /\n  AC-059b / REQ-055) preserved.\n- `./scripts/agent-verify.sh` run after meaningful edits (not\n  `dev/agent-verify.sh` — that path does not exist, F.0 reviewer\n  block #3).\n\n## 8. Out of scope for Pack 6.G\n\n- WAL2 mode. Branch-only SQLite; Pack 7 territory.\n- `libsqlite3-sys` replacement / vendor-SQLite path. Pack 7.\n- Reader/writer physical separation. Pack 7.\n- Schema/index changes (e.g. `canonical_nodes(write_cursor)`).\n- Any change that re-opens borrow/release pooling. F.0 is the\n  load-bearing topology for the entire G-phase.\n- Public Rust API expansion. `_for_test` accessors only with\n  `#[cfg(debug_assertions)]` per F.0 reviewer convention.\n\n## 9. Failure interpretation\n\nIf G.0 + G.1 + G.2 + G.3 all land KEEP and AC-020 still does not\nclose: ship 0.6.0 with REQ-020 deferred (per the F.0 packet-close\nposition) and open Pack 7 with the cumulative G-phase evidence as\nthe input.\n\nIf telemetry instead surfaces a **new** bottleneck class (e.g. a\nspecific hot path in `vec0` that is amenable to a SQL or query-\nplan tweak), the orchestrator may add a G.4 phase by appending to\nthis handoff and the STATUS phase-results table — same review +\nTDD discipline applies.\n\n## 10. Spawning interventions\n\nUse the resume §4 spawn block with anti-chaining defenses. Per-\nphase prompts live alongside this handoff:\n\n- `dev/plan/prompts/G0-wal-checkpoint-telemetry.md`\n- `dev/plan/prompts/G1-reader-lookaside.md` (authored after G.0)\n- `dev/plan/prompts/G2-per-worker-stmt-cache.md` (authored after\n  G.0 / G.1 KEEP)\n- `dev/plan/prompts/G3-checkpoint-tuning.md` (authored after\n  G.0 / G.1 / G.2)\n\nImplementer model: Opus 4.7 high. Reviewer: codex `gpt-5.4` high.\nWorktree pattern: `/tmp/fdb-pack6G-<phase>-<ts>`. Branch:\n`pack6G-<phase>-<ts>`.\n\n## 11. Pause points\n\n- After G.0 returns. Orchestrator reviews telemetry JSON, picks\n  next-phase ordering, and pauses for human review before\n  spawning G.1.\n- After each KEEP / REVERT decision (§3 update protocol in\n  `01-orchestrator-resume.md`).\n- After packet close (cumulative-vs-F.0 + cumulative-vs-Pack-5\n  numbers in the final synthesis JSON).\n\n## Update log\n\n- 2026-05-04 — Authored from the user's \"Best next opportunities\n  on top of F.0\" briefing. G.0 telemetry first; default ordering\n  G.1 → G.2 → G.3; Pack 6 F.0 baseline `a00cd13` (seq 531 ms /\n  conc 155 ms / speedup 3.49× / N=5).\n","numLines":247,"startLine":1,"totalLines":247}}}
dev/plans/runs/G3_5-cache-pressure-telemetry-20260504T144523Z.log:82:{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01CQpbp66HhoogP1aD9hVepE","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t{\n2\t  \"phase\": \"G.1\",\n3\t  \"decision_self\": \"INCONCLUSIVE\",\n4\t  \"decision_self_rationale\": \"AC-017 + AC-018 stayed green. Concurrent_median improved 168 ms -> 161 ms (-7 ms, ~4.2%) and speedup_median improved 3.339x -> 3.530x (+0.191x, no ratio worsening). Per handoff §6 / §8 the KEEP threshold is `concurrent_median < baseline - 1*stddev` = 168 - 11.89 = 156.11 ms; observed 161 ms misses the threshold by 4.89 ms (less than half a stddev). Movement is in the right direction but inside the noise band, so the implementer self-decision is INCONCLUSIVE. Lookaside-applied evidence captured below for the orchestrator + codex `gpt-5.4` high reviewer to confirm KEEP-or-REVERT.\",\n5\t  \"commit_sha\": \"46e3576ba92047b68d1a8c8163e580e065871d8d\",\n6\t  \"branch\": \"pack6G-G1-20260504T135138Z\",\n7\t  \"host_caveat\": \"Same worktree host as G.0 (Linux 5.15-tegra, schedutil, ~3x slower than the Pack 5 reference machine). Cross-pack comparisons should use ratios, not absolute ms.\",\n8\t  \"red_tests_written\": [\n9\t    {\n10\t      \"name\": \"reader_workers_have_lookaside_configured_with_ok_rc\",\n11\t      \"file\": \"src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/tests/reader_pool.rs\",\n12\t      \"red_failure_mode\": \"Compile-time: method `reader_lookaside_config_rcs_for_test` does not exist on `fathomdb_engine::Engine` (E0599). Pre-implementation. Asserts the rc of `sqlite3_db_config(LOOKASIDE)` captured at open time is SQLITE_OK (0) for every reader worker.\"\n13\t    },\n14\t    {\n15\t      \"name\": \"reader_workers_consume_lookaside_slots_after_warmup_read\",\n16\t      \"file\": \"src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/tests/reader_pool.rs\",\n17\t      \"red_failure_mode\": \"Compile-time: method `reader_lookaside_used_per_worker_for_test` does not exist on `fathomdb_engine::Engine` (E0599). Pre-implementation. Once compiling, this test would also fail at runtime if lookaside were misconfigured (e.g. ordered after a PRAGMA so SQLite silently ignored it) because `SQLITE_DBSTATUS_LOOKASIDE_USED` hiwtr would remain 0 after warmup. Initially also failed at runtime when the test read `current` instead of `hiwtr` (slots returned to the pool when the search transaction closed) — fixed by asserting on hiwtr, which is the right semantic for 'at least one slot was honored at any point'.\"\n18\t    }\n19\t  ],\n20\t  \"lookaside_config\": {\n21\t    \"slot_size_bytes\": 1200,\n22\t    \"slot_count\": 500,\n23\t    \"applied_via\": \"raw FFI: rusqlite::ffi::sqlite3_db_config(handle, ffi::SQLITE_DBCONFIG_LOOKASIDE, NULL, 1200, 500). rusqlite 0.31's safe `set_db_config` wrapper only supports the boolean DbConfig::* variants; `SQLITE_DBCONFIG_LOOKASIDE` is explicitly commented out in `rusqlite-0.31.0/src/config.rs`. Used the named symbol `ffi::SQLITE_DBCONFIG_LOOKASIDE` (= 1001) rather than a magic number per cross-platform Rust convention.\",\n24\t    \"ordering_assertion_rc\": \"0 (SQLITE_OK) for every reader worker, captured at open time before any PRAGMA / prepare ran on the connection. Captured per-worker into `Engine::reader_lookaside_rcs: Vec<i32>` (allow(dead_code) in release; read by `reader_lookaside_config_rcs_for_test` in debug).\"\n25\t  },\n26\t  \"lookaside_used_evidence\": {\n27\t    \"method\": \"Debug-only `ReaderRequest::LookasideStatus` request broadcast to every worker (not round-robin); each worker calls `sqlite3_db_status(SQLITE_DBSTATUS_LOOKASIDE_USED)` and returns the high-water-mark out-param. `current` was tried first but decays as transactions finalize so it is unreliable for post-warmup evidence; `hiwtr` is the correct latched signal that lookaside was honored at any point.\",\n28\t    \"after_warmup_test_workload\": \"READER_POOL_SIZE * 8 = 64 dispatched `engine.search('warmup')` calls (each routed round-robin to one of the 8 workers) on a fresh empty engine, search() returns Err but still parses + prepares + steps which exercises the lookaside arena.\",\n29\t    \"hiwtr_per_worker\": [57, 57, 57, 57, 57, 57, 57, 57],\n30\t    \"interpretation\": \"Every worker has hiwtr=57 slots used (well below the configured 500-slot capacity, ~11%). Uniformity across workers reflects the round-robin dispatch + the fact that `engine.search('warmup')` exercises the same transaction shape on each. AC-020's hybrid retrieval workload is more allocation-heavy and would push hiwtr higher; the test gate is 'consumed > 0', not 'saturated'.\"\n31\t  },\n32\t  \"ac017_runs\": [\n33\t    {\n34\t      \"passed\": true,\n35\t      \"profile\": \"release\",\n36\t      \"notes\": \"Run via `cargo test --release -p fathomdb-engine --test perf_gates -- ac_017 ac_018 --nocapture`; `test ac_017_vector_projection_freshness_p99_le_five_seconds ... ok` in 14.64 s wall.\"\n37\t    }\n38\t  ],\n39\t  \"ac018_runs\": [\n40\t    {\n41\t      \"drain_ms\": 95,\n42\t      \"passed\": true,\n43\t      \"notes\": \"release; AC018_NUMBERS drain_ms=95; well under the 2 s gate. Slightly higher than G.0's 51 ms (run-to-run; G.0 itself reported 56 ms in F.0 baseline).\"\n44\t    }\n45\t  ],\n46\t  \"ac020_runs\": [\n47\t    {\"run\": 1, \"sequential_ms\": 582, \"concurrent_ms\": 153, \"bound_ms\": 109, \"speedup\": 3.804, \"passed_5_33x\": false, \"passed_packet_1_25_margin\": false},\n48\t    {\"run\": 2, \"sequential_ms\": 547, \"concurrent_ms\": 161, \"bound_ms\": 102, \"speedup\": 3.398, \"passed_5_33x\": false, \"passed_packet_1_25_margin\": false},\n49\t    {\"run\": 3, \"sequential_ms\": 593, \"concurrent_ms\": 168, \"bound_ms\": 111, \"speedup\": 3.530, \"passed_5_33x\": false, \"passed_packet_1_25_margin\": false},\n50\t    {\"run\": 4, \"sequential_ms\": 563, \"concurrent_ms\": 181, \"bound_ms\": 105, \"speedup\": 3.110, \"passed_5_33x\": false, \"passed_packet_1_25_margin\": false},\n51\t    {\"run\": 5, \"sequential_ms\": 503, \"concurrent_ms\": 118, \"bound_ms\": 94,  \"speedup\": 4.263, \"passed_5_33x\": false, \"passed_packet_1_25_margin\": false}\n52\t  ],\n53\t  \"ac020_summary\": {\n54\t    \"sequential_ms\": {\"min\": 503, \"median\": 563, \"max\": 593, \"stddev\": 33.40},\n55\t    \"concurrent_ms\": {\"min\": 118, \"median\": 161, \"max\": 181, \"stddev\": 22.83},\n56\t    \"speedup\":      {\"min\": 3.110, \"median\": 3.530, \"max\": 4.263, \"stddev\": 0.428}\n57\t  },\n58\t  \"comparison_to_g0_baseline\": {\n59\t    \"g0_baseline_of_record\": {\n60\t      \"sequential_ms_median\": 552,\n61\t      \"concurrent_ms_median\": 168,\n62\t      \"speedup_median\": 3.339,\n63\t      \"concurrent_ms_stddev\": 11.89,\n64\t      \"n\": 5\n65\t    },\n66\t    \"g1_observed\": {\n67\t      \"sequential_ms_median\": 563,\n68\t      \"concurrent_ms_median\": 161,\n69\t      \"speedup_median\": 3.530,\n70\t      \"concurrent_ms_stddev\": 22.83,\n71\t      \"n\": 5\n72\t    },\n73\t    \"deltas\": {\n74\t      \"sequential_ms_median_delta\": \"+11 ms (+2.0%) — within run-to-run noise\",\n75\t      \"concurrent_ms_median_delta\": \"-7 ms (-4.2%) — improvement, but inside G.0's 1*stddev band (11.89 ms)\",\n76\t      \"speedup_median_delta\": \"+0.191x (+5.7%) — no ratio worsening\",\n77\t      \"concurrent_ms_stddev_delta\": \"+10.94 ms — G.1 run shows higher variance, partly driven by run 5 (118 ms) and run 4 (181 ms); not a regression but a wider band that loosens the KEEP threshold further on this sample\"\n78\t    },\n79\t    \"keep_threshold_evaluation\": {\n80\t      \"rule\": \"concurrent_median < g0_baseline.concurrent_median - 1 * g0_baseline.stddev\",\n81\t      \"threshold_ms\": 156.11,\n82\t      \"observed_ms\": 161,\n83\t      \"verdict\": \"miss by 4.89 ms (~0.41 * stddev); does NOT meet KEEP threshold\",\n84\t      \"ratio_floor_evaluation\": {\n85\t        \"rule\": \"speedup_median >= g0_baseline.speedup_median\",\n86\t        \"threshold\": 3.339,\n87\t        \"observed\": 3.530,\n88\t        \"verdict\": \"pass; no ratio worsening\"\n89\t      }\n90\t    }\n91\t  },\n92\t  \"optional_sweep_results\": null,\n93\t  \"optional_sweep_notes\": \"Did not run the [128, 250, 500, 1000] x {512, 1200} sweep grid. Spec §2 makes it optional ('do NOT bake the sweep into the production code path'); G.0 telemetry already pointed at 1200 x 500 as the right canonical sizing for the sticky reader topology and the small-allocation footprint of the FTS5 / vec0 hot stacks. If the orchestrator + reviewer want the sweep before deciding KEEP vs INCONCLUSIVE, it can be done as a follow-up under a debug-gated env knob without re-opening the public surface; the lookaside-call helper is already isolated in `configure_reader_lookaside`.\",\n94\t  \"unexpected_observations\": [\n95\t    \"AC-020 run-to-run variance widened on this G.1 sample (concurrent stddev 22.83 ms vs G.0's 11.89 ms). Run 5 in particular hit 118 ms / 4.263x — the best concurrent number observed in any G-phase run on this host so far — while run 4 hit 181 ms / 3.110x. The wider band loosens the formal KEEP threshold but suggests lookaside is doing real work when contention is the bottleneck (run 5 is plausibly an arena-pressure best-case). A larger N (e.g. N=10) would tighten the verdict; the spec calls for N=5 so I did not run more.\",\n96\t    \"Sequential_median moved +11 ms (552 -> 563). Within noise, but consistent with the documented 'lookaside has a small overhead per allocation when the slot pool is healthy' note in the SQLite docs; sequential perf shouldn't IMPROVE from lookaside on a single-threaded fixture (no malloc-arena contention to remove), and a small regression in the 1-2% band is expected and tolerable.\",\n97\t    \"Per-worker `LOOKASIDE_USED` hiwtr after warmup is uniform at 57 slots/worker, which is ~11% of the 500-slot capacity. AC-020's hybrid retrieval workload would push that higher (the warmup test does only a 64-call light-search loop on an empty DB). Slot_count 500 may be over-provisioned for the warmup fixture but well-sized for AC-020 + the FTS5/vec0 stacks visible in the G.0 top-call-site table. No evidence of a `LOOKASIDE_MISS_FULL` wall.\",\n98\t    \"AC-018 drain_ms moved from 51 ms (G.0 release run) to 95 ms (G.1 release run). Still trivially under the 2 s gate, no contract impact, but worth noting if the 6.G synthesis tracks AC-018 trend. Likely host-jitter; the writer connection does NOT have lookaside applied in this packet (G.1 scope is reader-side only).\"\n99\t  ],\n100\t  \"alternative_hypothesis_if_revert\": \"If a follow-on run on the orchestrator side shows the concurrent_median improvement does NOT reproduce (i.e. observed median > 168 + 1 * stddev), the most likely explanation is that the dominant residual on AC-020 is NOT the glibc malloc-arena mutex but the SQLite pcache1 global mutex (G.0 reported `page_cache` = 6.29% conc with 4.01x ratio, the second-largest contention class). Lookaside reduces calls to `pcache1Alloc -> sqlite3Malloc -> __libc_malloc` but does NOT eliminate the pcache1 mutex itself, which still sits on the page-fetch hot path. Per the G.0 unexpected_observations, a per-connection (private) page cache (`PRAGMA private_cache=ON` / `SQLITE_OPEN_PRIVATECACHE`) would attack that residual; that's a candidate G.4. The G.1 numbers being just below the 1*stddev threshold are consistent with this: lookaside removed some malloc-arena calls but the pcache1-mutex floor is still there.\",\n101\t  \"data_for_pivot\": {\n102\t    \"if_keep\": {\n103\t      \"next_lever\": \"G.4 — per-connection (private) page cache. G.0 telemetry called this out: page_cache (pcache1Fetch / Unpin / Alloc / Destroy) shows 4.01x growth concurrent vs sequential and is the second-largest contention path after allocator_lookaside. Lookaside masks pcache1Alloc fall-through to malloc but not the pcache1 global mutex itself. Canonical-SQLite lever: `SQLITE_OPEN_PRIVATECACHE` open flag or `PRAGMA cache=private` per-reader-connection. Distinct from the §3 do-not-retry `cache_size` global tuning entry.\",\n104\t      \"deferred\": \"G.2 (per-worker prepared-statement cache, sticky-connection revisit of E.1) is still motivated by parse_compile = 22.52% conc, but its ratio is 0.61 (share shrinks under concurrency), so it lowers a CPU floor more than it removes a contention point. Defer until G.4 settles.\"\n105\t    },\n106\t    \"if_revert_or_inconclusive\": {\n107\t      \"recommended_orchestrator_action\": \"Run an independent N=5 confirmation pass on the same commit with the same agent-verify-style guardrails. If the second pass reproduces concurrent_median ~ 161 ms (one stddev above the KEEP threshold), this is genuinely lookaside-improving-allocator-pressure but the F.0 baseline's 11.89 ms stddev was tighter than reality; KEEP on a relaxed 'concurrent_median < baseline AND speedup_median > baseline' rule is defensible (movement direction + ratio floor both pass). If the second pass shows no movement or regression, REVERT and pivot directly to G.4 (private page cache) since allocator-arena is then NOT the rate-limiting residual on this host.\",\n108\t      \"reviewer_specific_notes_for_codex_gpt54_high\": \"Lookaside is not on the §5 do-not-retry list. No public Rust API expansion: only `#[cfg(debug_assertions)] #[doc(hidden)]` test accessors per F.0 reviewer convention, and one debug-only `ReaderRequest` variant. FFI uses `c_int` per `feedback_cross_platform_rust.md`; named symbol `ffi::SQLITE_DBCONFIG_LOOKASIDE` not magic 1001. Ordering rc captured + debug-asserted before any PRAGMA / prepare runs. AC-018 unchanged (still green, drain 95 ms). Same-snapshot cursor contract / AC-021 / AC-022 / AC-059b untouched (no read-path SQL or transaction-shape changes).\"\n109\t    }\n110\t  },\n111\t  \"agent_verify_status\": \"pass\",\n112\t  \"agent_verify_reason\": \"`./scripts/agent-verify.sh` (per F.0 reviewer block #3 — NOT `dev/agent-verify.sh`) returned rc=0 on a clean run. First fmt run flagged a rustfmt-style block-vs-inline struct expansion on the new `LookasideStatus` ReaderRequest variant; fixed by running `cargo fmt --all` and re-running. AC-017 + AC-018 release-profile runs both green prior to the AC-020 capture (AC018_NUMBERS drain_ms=95).\",\n113\t  \"do_not_retry_cross_check\": [\n114\t    {\"item\": \"B.1 runtime sqlite3_config(SQLITE_CONFIG_MULTITHREAD)\",                 \"did_not_re_run\": true, \"evidence\": \"G.1 only adds `sqlite3_db_config(SQLITE_DBCONFIG_LOOKASIDE)` — a per-connection allocator setting. No `sqlite3_config` (capital-C global) calls were added or modified. `git log -p f1e66bc..46e3576 -- src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs` shows no SQLITE_CONFIG_MULTITHREAD touch.\"},\n115\t    {\"item\": \"C.1 compile-time SQLITE_THREADSAFE=2 rebuild\",                          \"did_not_re_run\": true, \"evidence\": \"No libsqlite3-sys / build.rs / Cargo.toml feature changes; canonical SQLite serialized mode unchanged. No reproducible-bin layer touched.\"},\n116\t    {\"item\": \"E.1 read-path prepare_cached on borrow/release pool connections\",      \"did_not_re_run\": true, \"evidence\": \"No prepare_cached changes anywhere in this commit. G.2 (sticky thread-affine prepared cache) is still future-packet.\"},\n117\t    {\"item\": \"Reader cache_size / mmap_size global tuning\",                          \"did_not_re_run\": true, \"evidence\": \"No PRAGMA cache_size / mmap_size production-default changes. Only PRAGMAs touched on reader connections at open are the pre-existing journal_mode=WAL + query_only=ON; nothing added.\"},\n118\t    {\"item\": \"Reader open flags READ_ONLY | NO_MUTEX\",                               \"did_not_re_run\": true, \"evidence\": \"Reader open flags untouched: still `Connection::open(&path)` with default flags. Lookaside is a per-connection allocator setting, not an open-flag bit; the §3 NO_MUTEX entry is unrelated and stays not-retried.\"}\n119\t  ],\n120\t  \"tests_run\": [\n121\t    \"cargo build --tests -p fathomdb-engine — green\",\n122\t    \"cargo test -p fathomdb-engine --test reader_pool (6 tests, all green; 2 new G.1 lookaside tests + the 4 existing F.0 worker-pool tests)\",\n123\t    \"cargo test --release -p fathomdb-engine --test perf_gates -- ac_017 ac_018 --nocapture — both green; AC018_NUMBERS drain_ms=95\",\n124\t    \"AGENT_LONG=1 cargo test --release -p fathomdb-engine --test perf_gates ac_020_reads_do_not_serialize -- --nocapture --test-threads=1 (x5) — gate fails as expected (still chasing 5.33x), all numerics captured\",\n125\t    \"cargo clippy --all-targets -- -D warnings — clean\",\n126\t    \"cargo fmt --all -- --check — clean\",\n127\t    \"./scripts/agent-verify.sh — rc=0\"\n128\t  ],\n129\t  \"next_phase_input\": {\n130\t    \"for_orchestrator\": \"Codex `gpt-5.4` high reviewer mandatory on this INCONCLUSIVE per handoff §7. If the reviewer + orchestrator KEEP, pivot to G.4 (private page cache) — that lever attacks the second-largest G.0 contention class (`page_cache` 6.29% conc with 4.01x ratio) and is canonical-SQLite (`SQLITE_OPEN_PRIVATECACHE` / `PRAGMA cache=private`), distinct from the §3 do-not-retry `cache_size` global tuning entry. If the reviewer REVERTS, the same G.4 candidate becomes the next phase since the residual is then NOT allocator-arena.\",\n131\t    \"for_packet_close\": \"G.1 is a small-radius lever; if it KEEPs the cumulative speedup vs F.0 is ~+0.19x (3.339x -> 3.530x). AC-020's 5.33x KEEP target / 5.0x packet floor is still ~1.5-1.8x away. Per handoff §9, packet success is 'every canonical-SQLite lever tried, KEEPs landed, residual gap documented for Pack 7' — not 'AC-020 closes within 0.6.0'.\"\n132\t  }\n133\t}\n134\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"485c34a8-dceb-42a9-9d76-fb4335ae2dfc","uuid":"79e8b266-161c-4a4b-82a0-bc9349c96d40","timestamp":"2026-05-04T14:45:55.017Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/tmp/fdb-pack6G-G3_5-20260504T144523Z/dev/plan/runs/G1-reader-lookaside-output.json","content":"{\n  \"phase\": \"G.1\",\n  \"decision_self\": \"INCONCLUSIVE\",\n  \"decision_self_rationale\": \"AC-017 + AC-018 stayed green. Concurrent_median improved 168 ms -> 161 ms (-7 ms, ~4.2%) and speedup_median improved 3.339x -> 3.530x (+0.191x, no ratio worsening). Per handoff §6 / §8 the KEEP threshold is `concurrent_median < baseline - 1*stddev` = 168 - 11.89 = 156.11 ms; observed 161 ms misses the threshold by 4.89 ms (less than half a stddev). Movement is in the right direction but inside the noise band, so the implementer self-decision is INCONCLUSIVE. Lookaside-applied evidence captured below for the orchestrator + codex `gpt-5.4` high reviewer to confirm KEEP-or-REVERT.\",\n  \"commit_sha\": \"46e3576ba92047b68d1a8c8163e580e065871d8d\",\n  \"branch\": \"pack6G-G1-20260504T135138Z\",\n  \"host_caveat\": \"Same worktree host as G.0 (Linux 5.15-tegra, schedutil, ~3x slower than the Pack 5 reference machine). Cross-pack comparisons should use ratios, not absolute ms.\",\n  \"red_tests_written\": [\n    {\n      \"name\": \"reader_workers_have_lookaside_configured_with_ok_rc\",\n      \"file\": \"src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/tests/reader_pool.rs\",\n      \"red_failure_mode\": \"Compile-time: method `reader_lookaside_config_rcs_for_test` does not exist on `fathomdb_engine::Engine` (E0599). Pre-implementation. Asserts the rc of `sqlite3_db_config(LOOKASIDE)` captured at open time is SQLITE_OK (0) for every reader worker.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"name\": \"reader_workers_consume_lookaside_slots_after_warmup_read\",\n      \"file\": \"src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/tests/reader_pool.rs\",\n      \"red_failure_mode\": \"Compile-time: method `reader_lookaside_used_per_worker_for_test` does not exist on `fathomdb_engine::Engine` (E0599). Pre-implementation. Once compiling, this test would also fail at runtime if lookaside were misconfigured (e.g. ordered after a PRAGMA so SQLite silently ignored it) because `SQLITE_DBSTATUS_LOOKASIDE_USED` hiwtr would remain 0 after warmup. Initially also failed at runtime when the test read `current` instead of `hiwtr` (slots returned to the pool when the search transaction closed) — fixed by asserting on hiwtr, which is the right semantic for 'at least one slot was honored at any point'.\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"lookaside_config\": {\n    \"slot_size_bytes\": 1200,\n    \"slot_count\": 500,\n    \"applied_via\": \"raw FFI: rusqlite::ffi::sqlite3_db_config(handle, ffi::SQLITE_DBCONFIG_LOOKASIDE, NULL, 1200, 500). rusqlite 0.31's safe `set_db_config` wrapper only supports the boolean DbConfig::* variants; `SQLITE_DBCONFIG_LOOKASIDE` is explicitly commented out in `rusqlite-0.31.0/src/config.rs`. Used the named symbol `ffi::SQLITE_DBCONFIG_LOOKASIDE` (= 1001) rather than a magic number per cross-platform Rust convention.\",\n    \"ordering_assertion_rc\": \"0 (SQLITE_OK) for every reader worker, captured at open time before any PRAGMA / prepare ran on the connection. Captured per-worker into `Engine::reader_lookaside_rcs: Vec<i32>` (allow(dead_code) in release; read by `reader_lookaside_config_rcs_for_test` in debug).\"\n  },\n  \"lookaside_used_evidence\": {\n    \"method\": \"Debug-only `ReaderRequest::LookasideStatus` request broadcast to every worker (not round-robin); each worker calls `sqlite3_db_status(SQLITE_DBSTATUS_LOOKASIDE_USED)` and returns the high-water-mark out-param. `current` was tried first but decays as transactions finalize so it is unreliable for post-warmup evidence; `hiwtr` is the correct latched signal that lookaside was honored at any point.\",\n    \"after_warmup_test_workload\": \"READER_POOL_SIZE * 8 = 64 dispatched `engine.search('warmup')` calls (each routed round-robin to one of the 8 workers) on a fresh empty engine, search() returns Err but still parses + prepares + steps which exercises the lookaside arena.\",\n    \"hiwtr_per_worker\": [57, 57, 57, 57, 57, 57, 57, 57],\n    \"interpretation\": \"Every worker has hiwtr=57 slots used (well below the configured 500-slot capacity, ~11%). Uniformity across workers reflects the round-robin dispatch + the fact that `engine.search('warmup')` exercises the same transaction shape on each. AC-020's hybrid retrieval workload is more allocation-heavy and would push hiwtr higher; the test gate is 'consumed > 0', not 'saturated'.\"\n  },\n  \"ac017_runs\": [\n    {\n      \"passed\": true,\n      \"profile\": \"release\",\n      \"notes\": \"Run via `cargo test --release -p fathomdb-engine --test perf_gates -- ac_017 ac_018 --nocapture`; `test ac_017_vector_projection_freshness_p99_le_five_seconds ... ok` in 14.64 s wall.\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"ac018_runs\": [\n    {\n      \"drain_ms\": 95,\n      \"passed\": true,\n      \"notes\": \"release; AC018_NUMBERS drain_ms=95; well under the 2 s gate. Slightly higher than G.0's 51 ms (run-to-run; G.0 itself reported 56 ms in F.0 baseline).\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"ac020_runs\": [\n    {\"run\": 1, \"sequential_ms\": 582, \"concurrent_ms\": 153, \"bound_ms\": 109, \"speedup\": 3.804, \"passed_5_33x\": false, \"passed_packet_1_25_margin\": false},\n    {\"run\": 2, \"sequential_ms\": 547, \"concurrent_ms\": 161, \"bound_ms\": 102, \"speedup\": 3.398, \"passed_5_33x\": false, \"passed_packet_1_25_margin\": false},\n    {\"run\": 3, \"sequential_ms\": 593, \"concurrent_ms\": 168, \"bound_ms\": 111, \"speedup\": 3.530, \"passed_5_33x\": false, \"passed_packet_1_25_margin\": false},\n    {\"run\": 4, \"sequential_ms\": 563, \"concurrent_ms\": 181, \"bound_ms\": 105, \"speedup\": 3.110, \"passed_5_33x\": false, \"passed_packet_1_25_margin\": false},\n    {\"run\": 5, \"sequential_ms\": 503, \"concurrent_ms\": 118, \"bound_ms\": 94,  \"speedup\": 4.263, \"passed_5_33x\": false, \"passed_packet_1_25_margin\": false}\n  ],\n  \"ac020_summary\": {\n    \"sequential_ms\": {\"min\": 503, \"median\": 563, \"max\": 593, \"stddev\": 33.40},\n    \"concurrent_ms\": {\"min\": 118, \"median\": 161, \"max\": 181, \"stddev\": 22.83},\n    \"speedup\":      {\"min\": 3.110, \"median\": 3.530, \"max\": 4.263, \"stddev\": 0.428}\n  },\n  \"comparison_to_g0_baseline\": {\n    \"g0_baseline_of_record\": {\n      \"sequential_ms_median\": 552,\n      \"concurrent_ms_median\": 168,\n      \"speedup_median\": 3.339,\n      \"concurrent_ms_stddev\": 11.89,\n      \"n\": 5\n    },\n    \"g1_observed\": {\n      \"sequential_ms_median\": 563,\n      \"concurrent_ms_median\": 161,\n      \"speedup_median\": 3.530,\n      \"concurrent_ms_stddev\": 22.83,\n      \"n\": 5\n    },\n    \"deltas\": {\n      \"sequential_ms_median_delta\": \"+11 ms (+2.0%) — within run-to-run noise\",\n      \"concurrent_ms_median_delta\": \"-7 ms (-4.2%) — improvement, but inside G.0's 1*stddev band (11.89 ms)\",\n      \"speedup_median_delta\": \"+0.191x (+5.7%) — no ratio worsening\",\n      \"concurrent_ms_stddev_delta\": \"+10.94 ms — G.1 run shows higher variance, partly driven by run 5 (118 ms) and run 4 (181 ms); not a regression but a wider band that loosens the KEEP threshold further on this sample\"\n    },\n    \"keep_threshold_evaluation\": {\n      \"rule\": \"concurrent_median < g0_baseline.concurrent_median - 1 * g0_baseline.stddev\",\n      \"threshold_ms\": 156.11,\n      \"observed_ms\": 161,\n      \"verdict\": \"miss by 4.89 ms (~0.41 * stddev); does NOT meet KEEP threshold\",\n      \"ratio_floor_evaluation\": {\n        \"rule\": \"speedup_median >= g0_baseline.speedup_median\",\n        \"threshold\": 3.339,\n        \"observed\": 3.530,\n        \"verdict\": \"pass; no ratio worsening\"\n      }\n    }\n  },\n  \"optional_sweep_results\": null,\n  \"optional_sweep_notes\": \"Did not run the [128, 250, 500, 1000] x {512, 1200} sweep grid. Spec §2 makes it optional ('do NOT bake the sweep into the production code path'); G.0 telemetry already pointed at 1200 x 500 as the right canonical sizing for the sticky reader topology and the small-allocation footprint of the FTS5 / vec0 hot stacks. If the orchestrator + reviewer want the sweep before deciding KEEP vs INCONCLUSIVE, it can be done as a follow-up under a debug-gated env knob without re-opening the public surface; the lookaside-call helper is already isolated in `configure_reader_lookaside`.\",\n  \"unexpected_observations\": [\n    \"AC-020 run-to-run variance widened on this G.1 sample (concurrent stddev 22.83 ms vs G.0's 11.89 ms). Run 5 in particular hit 118 ms / 4.263x — the best concurrent number observed in any G-phase run on this host so far — while run 4 hit 181 ms / 3.110x. The wider band loosens the formal KEEP threshold but suggests lookaside is doing real work when contention is the bottleneck (run 5 is plausibly an arena-pressure best-case). A larger N (e.g. N=10) would tighten the verdict; the spec calls for N=5 so I did not run more.\",\n    \"Sequential_median moved +11 ms (552 -> 563). Within noise, but consistent with the documented 'lookaside has a small overhead per allocation when the slot pool is healthy' note in the SQLite docs; sequential perf shouldn't IMPROVE from lookaside on a single-threaded fixture (no malloc-arena contention to remove), and a small regression in the 1-2% band is expected and tolerable.\",\n    \"Per-worker `LOOKASIDE_USED` hiwtr after warmup is uniform at 57 slots/worker, which is ~11% of the 500-slot capacity. AC-020's hybrid retrieval workload would push that higher (the warmup test does only a 64-call light-search loop on an empty DB). Slot_count 500 may be over-provisioned for the warmup fixture but well-sized for AC-020 + the FTS5/vec0 stacks visible in the G.0 top-call-site table. No evidence of a `LOOKASIDE_MISS_FULL` wall.\",\n    \"AC-018 drain_ms moved from 51 ms (G.0 release run) to 95 ms (G.1 release run). Still trivially under the 2 s gate, no contract impact, but worth noting if the 6.G synthesis tracks AC-018 trend. Likely host-jitter; the writer connection does NOT have lookaside applied in this packet (G.1 scope is reader-side only).\"\n  ],\n  \"alternative_hypothesis_if_revert\": \"If a follow-on run on the orchestrator side shows the concurrent_median improvement does NOT reproduce (i.e. observed median > 168 + 1 * stddev), the most likely explanation is that the dominant residual on AC-020 is NOT the glibc malloc-arena mutex but the SQLite pcache1 global mutex (G.0 reported `page_cache` = 6.29% conc with 4.01x ratio, the second-largest contention class). Lookaside reduces calls to `pcache1Alloc -> sqlite3Malloc -> __libc_malloc` but does NOT eliminate the pcache1 mutex itself, which still sits on the page-fetch hot path. Per the G.0 unexpected_observations, a per-connection (private) page cache (`PRAGMA private_cache=ON` / `SQLITE_OPEN_PRIVATECACHE`) would attack that residual; that's a candidate G.4. The G.1 numbers being just below the 1*stddev threshold are consistent with this: lookaside removed some malloc-arena calls but the pcache1-mutex floor is still there.\",\n  \"data_for_pivot\": {\n    \"if_keep\": {\n      \"next_lever\": \"G.4 — per-connection (private) page cache. G.0 telemetry called this out: page_cache (pcache1Fetch / Unpin / Alloc / Destroy) shows 4.01x growth concurrent vs sequential and is the second-largest contention path after allocator_lookaside. Lookaside masks pcache1Alloc fall-through to malloc but not the pcache1 global mutex itself. Canonical-SQLite lever: `SQLITE_OPEN_PRIVATECACHE` open flag or `PRAGMA cache=private` per-reader-connection. Distinct from the §3 do-not-retry `cache_size` global tuning entry.\",\n      \"deferred\": \"G.2 (per-worker prepared-statement cache, sticky-connection revisit of E.1) is still motivated by parse_compile = 22.52% conc, but its ratio is 0.61 (share shrinks under concurrency), so it lowers a CPU floor more than it removes a contention point. Defer until G.4 settles.\"\n    },\n    \"if_revert_or_inconclusive\": {\n      \"recommended_orchestrator_action\": \"Run an independent N=5 confirmation pass on the same commit with the same agent-verify-style guardrails. If the second pass reproduces concurrent_median ~ 161 ms (one stddev above the KEEP threshold), this is genuinely lookaside-improving-allocator-pressure but the F.0 baseline's 11.89 ms stddev was tighter than reality; KEEP on a relaxed 'concurrent_median < baseline AND speedup_median > baseline' rule is defensible (movement direction + ratio floor both pass). If the second pass shows no movement or regression, REVERT and pivot directly to G.4 (private page cache) since allocator-arena is then NOT the rate-limiting residual on this host.\",\n      \"reviewer_specific_notes_for_codex_gpt54_high\": \"Lookaside is not on the §5 do-not-retry list. No public Rust API expansion: only `#[cfg(debug_assertions)] #[doc(hidden)]` test accessors per F.0 reviewer convention, and one debug-only `ReaderRequest` variant. FFI uses `c_int` per `feedback_cross_platform_rust.md`; named symbol `ffi::SQLITE_DBCONFIG_LOOKASIDE` not magic 1001. Ordering rc captured + debug-asserted before any PRAGMA / prepare runs. AC-018 unchanged (still green, drain 95 ms). Same-snapshot cursor contract / AC-021 / AC-022 / AC-059b untouched (no read-path SQL or transaction-shape changes).\"\n    }\n  },\n  \"agent_verify_status\": \"pass\",\n  \"agent_verify_reason\": \"`./scripts/agent-verify.sh` (per F.0 reviewer block #3 — NOT `dev/agent-verify.sh`) returned rc=0 on a clean run. First fmt run flagged a rustfmt-style block-vs-inline struct expansion on the new `LookasideStatus` ReaderRequest variant; fixed by running `cargo fmt --all` and re-running. AC-017 + AC-018 release-profile runs both green prior to the AC-020 capture (AC018_NUMBERS drain_ms=95).\",\n  \"do_not_retry_cross_check\": [\n    {\"item\": \"B.1 runtime sqlite3_config(SQLITE_CONFIG_MULTITHREAD)\",                 \"did_not_re_run\": true, \"evidence\": \"G.1 only adds `sqlite3_db_config(SQLITE_DBCONFIG_LOOKASIDE)` — a per-connection allocator setting. No `sqlite3_config` (capital-C global) calls were added or modified. `git log -p f1e66bc..46e3576 -- src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs` shows no SQLITE_CONFIG_MULTITHREAD touch.\"},\n    {\"item\": \"C.1 compile-time SQLITE_THREADSAFE=2 rebuild\",                          \"did_not_re_run\": true, \"evidence\": \"No libsqlite3-sys / build.rs / Cargo.toml feature changes; canonical SQLite serialized mode unchanged. No reproducible-bin layer touched.\"},\n    {\"item\": \"E.1 read-path prepare_cached on borrow/release pool connections\",      \"did_not_re_run\": true, \"evidence\": \"No prepare_cached changes anywhere in this commit. G.2 (sticky thread-affine prepared cache) is still future-packet.\"},\n    {\"item\": \"Reader cache_size / mmap_size global tuning\",                          \"did_not_re_run\": true, \"evidence\": \"No PRAGMA cache_size / mmap_size production-default changes. Only PRAGMAs touched on reader connections at open are the pre-existing journal_mode=WAL + query_only=ON; nothing added.\"},\n    {\"item\": \"Reader open flags READ_ONLY | NO_MUTEX\",                               \"did_not_re_run\": true, \"evidence\": \"Reader open flags untouched: still `Connection::open(&path)` with default flags. Lookaside is a per-connection allocator setting, not an open-flag bit; the §3 NO_MUTEX entry is unrelated and stays not-retried.\"}\n  ],\n  \"tests_run\": [\n    \"cargo build --tests -p fathomdb-engine — green\",\n    \"cargo test -p fathomdb-engine --test reader_pool (6 tests, all green; 2 new G.1 lookaside tests + the 4 existing F.0 worker-pool tests)\",\n    \"cargo test --release -p fathomdb-engine --test perf_gates -- ac_017 ac_018 --nocapture — both green; AC018_NUMBERS drain_ms=95\",\n    \"AGENT_LONG=1 cargo test --release -p fathomdb-engine --test perf_gates ac_020_reads_do_not_serialize -- --nocapture --test-threads=1 (x5) — gate fails as expected (still chasing 5.33x), all numerics captured\",\n    \"cargo clippy --all-targets -- -D warnings — clean\",\n    \"cargo fmt --all -- --check — clean\",\n    \"./scripts/agent-verify.sh — rc=0\"\n  ],\n  \"next_phase_input\": {\n    \"for_orchestrator\": \"Codex `gpt-5.4` high reviewer mandatory on this INCONCLUSIVE per handoff §7. If the reviewer + orchestrator KEEP, pivot to G.4 (private page cache) — that lever attacks the second-largest G.0 contention class (`page_cache` 6.29% conc with 4.01x ratio) and is canonical-SQLite (`SQLITE_OPEN_PRIVATECACHE` / `PRAGMA cache=private`), distinct from the §3 do-not-retry `cache_size` global tuning entry. If the reviewer REVERTS, the same G.4 candidate becomes the next phase since the residual is then NOT allocator-arena.\",\n    \"for_packet_close\": \"G.1 is a small-radius lever; if it KEEPs the cumulative speedup vs F.0 is ~+0.19x (3.339x -> 3.530x). AC-020's 5.33x KEEP target / 5.0x packet floor is still ~1.5-1.8x away. Per handoff §9, packet success is 'every canonical-SQLite lever tried, KEEPs landed, residual gap documented for Pack 7' — not 'AC-020 closes within 0.6.0'.\"\n  }\n}\n","numLines":134,"startLine":1,"totalLines":134}}}
