2ms) — indicates 8 threads were running but most cycles were wasted in spinloops. Useful work (min_idx, vec0Filter) dropped from 14.5% to 8.7% of cycles.\",\n \"alternative_hypothesis\": \"The dominant bottleneck is NOT the lock hierarchy between read/write connections (as §6 hypothesis ladder suggests) but rather SQLite's internal WAL/pager spinlocks (**aarch64_swp4_rel, **aarch64_cas4_acq) plus the SQLite mutex (***pthread_mutex_lock) that serializes all writers. Even read-heavy concurrent workloads hit these because every query goes through sqlite3LockAndPrepare. A secondary opportunity is SQL re-parsing: sqlite3RunParser at 4-5% of cycles suggests prepared statements are not cached across calls.\",\n \"data_for_pivot\": \"If A.2 cannot isolate the specific spinlock being contended: (1) `perf lock` subcommand (needs kernel events, blocked by paranoid=2 — would need sudo); (2) `perf c2c` for cache-line false sharing detection (also needs kernel events); (3) add USDT probes to SQLite WAL acquire/release to measure hold times without kernel profiling; (4) run `strace -c -f` against both entry points to see syscall distribution — A.3 is already planned for this. The folded diff clearly shows the atomic/mutex excess in concurrent and should be sufficient for A.2 bottleneck classification.\",\n \"log_path\": \"dev/plans/runs/A1-perf-capture-output.json\",\n \"commit_sha\": \"fec71a0\",\n \"pre_flight_notes\": {\n \"perf_source\": \"Extracted from linux-tools-5.15.0-124-generic arm64.deb (ports.ubuntu.com) — no linux-tools-tegra package; version skew 5.15.163 vs 5.15.185 minor, no issues observed\",\n \"inferno_installed\": \"cargo install inferno v0.12.6\",\n \"build_command\": \"RUSTFLAGS='-C force-frame-pointers=yes' cargo build -p fathomdb-engine --release --test perf_gates\",\n \"build_note\": \"Used --test perf_gates (not --tests) to skip pre-existing compile errors in cursors/lifecycle_observability/compatibility tests noted by A.0\",\n \"cpu_governor\": \"Could 