dev/plans/runs/G1-reader-lookaside-20260504T135138Z.log:62:{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_014DE6wzyafunyBTKu57tCPo","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# Pack 6.G handoff — Canonical-SQLite tuning on the F.0 baseline\n2\t\n3\tPhase 9 Pack 6.G continues AC-020 closure work after Pack 6 closed\n4\tF.0 (thread-affine reader workers KEPT, human override of REVERT\n5\trule) on 2026-05-04. Pack 6.G stays inside canonical/release SQLite\n6\t— no WAL2, no `libsqlite3-sys` swap, no rusqlite replacement. Those\n7\tremain Pack 7+ research territory.\n8\t\n9\tF.0 removed Rust-side ReaderPool / cross-thread-handoff cost\n10\t(speedup 1.49×→3.49×, +2.34×). The residual gap is now plausibly\n11\tSQLite-internal: WAL shared-memory atomics, checkpoint pressure,\n12\tper-connection allocator (lookaside), and / or parse cost on\n13\tsticky long-lived reader connections. Pack 6.G attacks each of\n14\tthose with the smallest-radius, highest-evidence canonical-SQLite\n15\tlevers, in the order the telemetry pass picks.\n16\t\n17\t## 1. Read order on resume\n18\t\n19\t1. `dev/plan/runs/STATUS.md` — Pack 6 closed state + Pack 6.G\n20\t   active phase.\n21\t2. `dev/plan/runs/F0-thread-affine-readers-output.json` — F.0\n22\t   numeric baseline + worker pool topology summary.\n23\t3. `dev/plan/runs/F0-review-20260504T122055Z.md` — codex BLOCK\n24\t   findings + override rationale; key for future spawn discipline.\n25\t4. `dev/notes/performance-whitepaper-notes.md` §4 (kept) + §5\n26\t   (do-not-retry) + §11 (Pack 5 narrative). §5 still binds — no\n27\t   retry of B.1 / C.1 / E.1 without explicit override.\n28\t5. `dev/plan/prompts/01-orchestrator-resume.md` §4 — anti-chaining\n29\t   defenses (PREAMBLE + `--disallowedTools Task Agent` + stream-\n30\t   json). Apply on every spawn.\n31\t6. The next phase prompt per \"Next action\" in STATUS.md.\n32\t\n33\t## 2. State at this hand-off\n34\t\n35\t- Branch: `0.6.0-rewrite`. Tip: `a00cd13` at handoff creation.\n36\t- F.0 commits already on tip: `4ebdd68` (refactor) + `29cdc6f`\n37\t  (cfg-gate fix) + `a00cd13` (KEEP bookkeeping).\n38\t- AC-020 N=5 numbers (post-F.0, this host): seq 531 ms / conc\n39\t  155 ms / speedup 3.49×. Required ≥ 5.0× KEEP / ≤ 80 ms conc.\n40\t  Gap: 75 ms above conc bound; 1.51× below speedup floor.\n41\t- Host caveat: this worktree machine runs ~3× slower in absolute\n42\t  ms than the Pack 5 reference machine. Cross-pack comparisons\n43\t  use the speedup ratio, not absolute ms.\n44\t- AC-017, AC-018 green; AC-018 drain 56 ms.\n45\t- Active worktrees: none.\n46\t- Anti-chaining defenses verified WORKING on F.0 spawn (single\n47\t  coherent agent; no Task spawns). Keep on for all G-phase spawns.\n48\t\n49\t## 3. Pack 5 / Pack 6 falsifications you do not retry\n50\t\n51\tPer the whitepaper §5 do-not-retry list:\n52\t\n53\t- Runtime `sqlite3_config(SQLITE_CONFIG_MULTITHREAD)` (B.1).\n54\t- Compile-time `SQLITE_THREADSAFE=2` rebuild (C.1).\n55\t- Read-path `prepare_cached` on borrow/release pool connections\n56\t  (E.1). **Note:** G.2 in this packet revisits `prepare_cached` on\n57\t  the F.0 _thread-affine_ connections, which is a different\n58\t  topology and a different argument. Treat G.2 as new territory,\n59\t  not an §5 retry — see G.2 prompt for the explicit override\n60\t  rationale.\n61\t- Reader `cache_size` / `mmap_size` global tuning (Pack 5 reverted\n62\t  experiment ledger). G.0 may _measure_ mmap_size effects but does\n63\t  not change the production default.\n64\t- Reader open flags `READ_ONLY | NO_MUTEX`. G-phase keeps\n65\t  serialized open flags; thread-affine ownership is the safety\n66\t  argument, not the open-flag bits.\n67\t\n68\t## 4. Authorized G-phase interventions (in execution order)\n69\t\n70\t### G.0 — WAL / checkpoint telemetry pass (read-only)\n71\t\n72\tRe-capture AC-020 perf evidence on the F.0 tip with extended\n73\tsymbol grouping. Distinguish:\n74\t\n75\t- WAL shared-memory atomics (`walIndexMap`, `walFrames`, `walRead*`\n76\t  function family, atomic / CAS primitives inside `pager.c` / `wal.c`).\n77\t- Checkpoint cost (`sqlite3WalCheckpoint`, busy-handler interaction,\n78\t  auto-checkpoint threshold hits).\n79\t- Per-connection allocator behavior (`sqlite3MallocSize`,\n80\t  `sqlite3_release_memory`, lookaside hit/miss if surfaceable).\n81\t- Parse cost on sticky reader connections (`sqlite3RunParser`,\n82\t  `sqlite3VdbePrepare`). Should be high if E.1 hypothesis applies\n83\t  to F.0 topology; should be low if F.0 already amortized it.\n84\t- Our code share (engine + worker dispatch).\n85\t\n86\tOutput: classification JSON + a short reviewer-ready note picking\n87\tthe strongest single lever among G.1 / G.2 / G.3 for the next\n88\tphase. No production code change. No commit unless the diagnostic\n89\tadds a `#[ignore]`-gated counter test.\n90\t\n91\t### G.1 — Reader-worker lookaside tuning\n92\t\n93\tConfigure SQLite per-connection lookaside immediately after\n94\t`Connection::open` for each F.0 reader worker. Use\n95\t`sqlite3_db_config(SQLITE_DBCONFIG_LOOKASIDE, ...)` with\n96\tdocumented sane defaults (per https://www.sqlite.org/malloc.html\n97\t§3 — typical 1200-byte slots, 100 slots, sized for the workload's\n98\tprepared-statement footprint; revise from G.0 evidence).\n99\t\n100\tExpected impact (per SQLite docs): ~10–15% overall perf in\n101\tallocator-heavy workloads. Reader-side, expressed across N=8\n102\tworkers with sticky connections, is exactly the documented happy\n103\tpath. Sequential effect: small. Concurrent effect: small-to-\n104\tmedium if the allocator is contended.\n105\t\n106\tKEEP / REVERT decision rule lives in `G1-reader-lookaside.md`.\n107\tNumeric KEEP target: any clean, reproducible improvement on\n108\tconcurrent_median_ms with no AC-017 / AC-018 regression. Lookaside\n109\tis too small a lever to require AC-020 closure alone — it is a\n110\tsequencing decision, not a closer.\n111\t\n112\t### G.2 — Per-worker prepared-statement cache (sticky-connection revisit of E.1)\n113\t\n114\tE.1 (Pack 5) added `prepare_cached` on the four read-path search\n115\tstatements against borrow/release pool connections. Sequential\n116\timproved -13.7%, concurrent unchanged, ratio worsened, codex BLOCK\n117\ton public surface + decision-rule mismatch + partial test. REVERTED.\n118\t\n119\tThe F.0 topology _is_ the natural shape for prepared-statement\n120\tcaching: each reader worker owns one connection for its lifetime,\n121\tso the cache amortizes across the worker's full lifetime, not just\n122\tthe brief borrow window. G.2 re-runs that experiment with two\n123\tbinding constraints from E.1's review:\n124\t\n125\t- All four statements covered (no partial test).\n126\t- No public Rust API expansion. Use private worker-internal cache\n127\t  with an integration test that drives observable behavior, not a\n128\t  `pub fn ..._for_test` accessor unless it is `#[cfg(debug_assertions)]`-gated and explicitly justified in the diff.\n129\t\n130\tKEEP target: AC-020 numerics improve cleanly (no ratio worsening).\n131\tThe Pack 5 §5 entry binds: G.2 is not a retry of the same\n132\texperiment; it is the same SQL change applied to a strictly\n133\tdifferent connection-lifetime topology. Whitepaper §12 carries the\n134\texplicit override note.\n135\t\n136\t### G.3 — WAL checkpoint policy / tuning\n137\t\n138\tAdjust auto-checkpoint threshold (PRAGMA `wal_autocheckpoint`),\n139\tbusy timeout, or move to an explicit application-driven checkpoint\n140\tschedule on the writer side. If G.0 telemetry says checkpoint cost\n141\tis small or zero on the read-heavy fixture, G.3 may be SKIPPED in\n142\tthis packet and queued for a real-write-load packet.\n143\t\n144\tKEEP target: lower variance + lower max latency on AC-020\n145\tconcurrent runs without regressing AC-017 / AC-018.\n146\t\n147\t## 5. Phase ordering\n148\t\n149\t1. G.0 telemetry first. Picks strongest lever or surfaces a non-\n150\t   listed bottleneck (orchestrator pivot point).\n151\t2. Run interventions in the order G.0 picks. Default order is\n152\t   G.1 → G.2 → G.3.\n153\t3. After each intervention: KEEP or REVERT, then re-measure\n154\t   AC-020 N=5 and update the chained baseline-of-record.\n155\t4. Final synthesis at packet close: cumulative speedup vs F.0\n156\t   baseline (3.49×) and vs the original Pack 5 baseline (1.49×).\n157\t\n158\t## 6. Decision rules (per phase)\n159\t\n160\t- KEEP iff AC-017 + AC-018 stay green AND AC-020 numerics improve\n161\t  cleanly (no ratio worsening, no concurrent_median_ms regression\n162\t  outside one stddev) AND no contract / public-surface violation.\n163\t- INCONCLUSIVE iff numerics flat within noise; record evidence and\n164\t  move on.\n165\t- REVERT iff any of the above fails.\n166\t\n167\tThe packet-close success definition is **not** \"AC-020 closes\n168\twithin 0.6.0\". It is \"every canonical-SQLite lever has been tried,\n169\tKEEPs are landed, and the residual gap is documented well enough\n170\tthat Pack 7 (WAL2 / vendor-SQLite / reader-writer split) can be\n171\tscoped from evidence rather than guess.\"\n172\t\n173\t## 7. Reviewer requirements\n174\t\n175\tCodex `gpt-5.4` high reviewer **mandatory on KEEP / INCONCLUSIVE**\n176\tfor G.1 / G.2 / G.3. G.0 is read-only diagnostics — reviewer\n177\toptional unless it lands a counter test.\n178\t\n179\tReviewer must confirm per phase:\n180\t\n181\t- No retry of an §5 do-not-retry experiment without explicit\n182\t  override note in the prompt + whitepaper.\n183\t- No public Rust API expansion without ADR / interface-doc work,\n184\t  or `#[cfg(debug_assertions)]` gating with the existing convention.\n185\t- AC-018 unchanged; same-snapshot cursor contract (REQ-013 /\n186\t  AC-059b / REQ-055) preserved.\n187\t- `./scripts/agent-verify.sh` run after meaningful edits (not\n188\t  `dev/agent-verify.sh` — that path does not exist, F.0 reviewer\n189\t  block #3).\n190\t\n191\t## 8. Out of scope for Pack 6.G\n192\t\n193\t- WAL2 mode. Branch-only SQLite; Pack 7 territory.\n194\t- `libsqlite3-sys` replacement / vendor-SQLite path. Pack 7.\n195\t- Reader/writer physical separation. Pack 7.\n196\t- Schema/index changes (e.g. `canonical_nodes(write_cursor)`).\n197\t- Any change that re-opens borrow/release pooling. F.0 is the\n198\t  load-bearing topology for the entire G-phase.\n199\t- Public Rust API expansion. `_for_test` accessors only with\n200\t  `#[cfg(debug_assertions)]` per F.0 reviewer convention.\n201\t\n202\t## 9. Failure interpretation\n203\t\n204\tIf G.0 + G.1 + G.2 + G.3 all land KEEP and AC-020 still does not\n205\tclose: ship 0.6.0 with REQ-020 deferred (per the F.0 packet-close\n206\tposition) and open Pack 7 with the cumulative G-phase evidence as\n207\tthe input.\n208\t\n209\tIf telemetry instead surfaces a **new** bottleneck class (e.g. a\n210\tspecific hot path in `vec0` that is amenable to a SQL or query-\n211\tplan tweak), the orchestrator may add a G.4 phase by appending to\n212\tthis handoff and the STATUS phase-results table — same review +\n213\tTDD discipline applies.\n214\t\n215\t## 10. Spawning interventions\n216\t\n217\tUse the resume §4 spawn block with anti-chaining defenses. Per-\n218\tphase prompts live alongside this handoff:\n219\t\n220\t- `dev/plan/prompts/G0-wal-checkpoint-telemetry.md`\n221\t- `dev/plan/prompts/G1-reader-lookaside.md` (authored after G.0)\n222\t- `dev/plan/prompts/G2-per-worker-stmt-cache.md` (authored after\n223\t  G.0 / G.1 KEEP)\n224\t- `dev/plan/prompts/G3-checkpoint-tuning.md` (authored after\n225\t  G.0 / G.1 / G.2)\n226\t\n227\tImplementer model: Opus 4.7 high. Reviewer: codex `gpt-5.4` high.\n228\tWorktree pattern: `/tmp/fdb-pack6G-<phase>-<ts>`. Branch:\n229\t`pack6G-<phase>-<ts>`.\n230\t\n231\t## 11. Pause points\n232\t\n233\t- After G.0 returns. Orchestrator reviews telemetry JSON, picks\n234\t  next-phase ordering, and pauses for human review before\n235\t  spawning G.1.\n236\t- After each KEEP / REVERT decision (§3 update protocol in\n237\t  `01-orchestrator-resume.md`).\n238\t- After packet close (cumulative-vs-F.0 + cumulative-vs-Pack-5\n239\t  numbers in the final synthesis JSON).\n240\t\n241\t## Update log\n242\t\n243\t- 2026-05-04 — Authored from the user's \"Best next opportunities\n244\t  on top of F.0\" briefing. G.0 telemetry first; default ordering\n245\t  G.1 → G.2 → G.3; Pack 6 F.0 baseline `a00cd13` (seq 531 ms /\n246\t  conc 155 ms / speedup 3.49× / N=5).\n247\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"14d083b7-460f-4635-b7a8-5e1b3e7e8a72","uuid":"e969ac18-ec63-4119-ac09-1e0808a62045","timestamp":"2026-05-04T13:52:02.240Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/tmp/fdb-pack6G-G1-20260504T135138Z/dev/plan/prompts/04-pack6G-handoff-canonical-sqlite-tuning.md","content":"# Pack 6.G handoff — Canonical-SQLite tuning on the F.0 baseline\n\nPhase 9 Pack 6.G continues AC-020 closure work after Pack 6 closed\nF.0 (thread-affine reader workers KEPT, human override of REVERT\nrule) on 2026-05-04. Pack 6.G stays inside canonical/release SQLite\n— no WAL2, no `libsqlite3-sys` swap, no rusqlite replacement. Those\nremain Pack 7+ research territory.\n\nF.0 removed Rust-side ReaderPool / cross-thread-handoff cost\n(speedup 1.49×→3.49×, +2.34×). The residual gap is now plausibly\nSQLite-internal: WAL shared-memory atomics, checkpoint pressure,\nper-connection allocator (lookaside), and / or parse cost on\nsticky long-lived reader connections. Pack 6.G attacks each of\nthose with the smallest-radius, highest-evidence canonical-SQLite\nlevers, in the order the telemetry pass picks.\n\n## 1. Read order on resume\n\n1. `dev/plan/runs/STATUS.md` — Pack 6 closed state + Pack 6.G\n   active phase.\n2. `dev/plan/runs/F0-thread-affine-readers-output.json` — F.0\n   numeric baseline + worker pool topology summary.\n3. `dev/plan/runs/F0-review-20260504T122055Z.md` — codex BLOCK\n   findings + override rationale; key for future spawn discipline.\n4. `dev/notes/performance-whitepaper-notes.md` §4 (kept) + §5\n   (do-not-retry) + §11 (Pack 5 narrative). §5 still binds — no\n   retry of B.1 / C.1 / E.1 without explicit override.\n5. `dev/plan/prompts/01-orchestrator-resume.md` §4 — anti-chaining\n   defenses (PREAMBLE + `--disallowedTools Task Agent` + stream-\n   json). Apply on every spawn.\n6. The next phase prompt per \"Next action\" in STATUS.md.\n\n## 2. State at this hand-off\n\n- Branch: `0.6.0-rewrite`. Tip: `a00cd13` at handoff creation.\n- F.0 commits already on tip: `4ebdd68` (refactor) + `29cdc6f`\n  (cfg-gate fix) + `a00cd13` (KEEP bookkeeping).\n- AC-020 N=5 numbers (post-F.0, this host): seq 531 ms / conc\n  155 ms / speedup 3.49×. Required ≥ 5.0× KEEP / ≤ 80 ms conc.\n  Gap: 75 ms above conc bound; 1.51× below speedup floor.\n- Host caveat: this worktree machine runs ~3× slower in absolute\n  ms than the Pack 5 reference machine. Cross-pack comparisons\n  use the speedup ratio, not absolute ms.\n- AC-017, AC-018 green; AC-018 drain 56 ms.\n- Active worktrees: none.\n- Anti-chaining defenses verified WORKING on F.0 spawn (single\n  coherent agent; no Task spawns). Keep on for all G-phase spawns.\n\n## 3. Pack 5 / Pack 6 falsifications you do not retry\n\nPer the whitepaper §5 do-not-retry list:\n\n- Runtime `sqlite3_config(SQLITE_CONFIG_MULTITHREAD)` (B.1).\n- Compile-time `SQLITE_THREADSAFE=2` rebuild (C.1).\n- Read-path `prepare_cached` on borrow/release pool connections\n  (E.1). **Note:** G.2 in this packet revisits `prepare_cached` on\n  the F.0 _thread-affine_ connections, which is a different\n  topology and a different argument. Treat G.2 as new territory,\n  not an §5 retry — see G.2 prompt for the explicit override\n  rationale.\n- Reader `cache_size` / `mmap_size` global tuning (Pack 5 reverted\n  experiment ledger). G.0 may _measure_ mmap_size effects but does\n  not change the production default.\n- Reader open flags `READ_ONLY | NO_MUTEX`. G-phase keeps\n  serialized open flags; thread-affine ownership is the safety\n  argument, not the open-flag bits.\n\n## 4. Authorized G-phase interventions (in execution order)\n\n### G.0 — WAL / checkpoint telemetry pass (read-only)\n\nRe-capture AC-020 perf evidence on the F.0 tip with extended\nsymbol grouping. Distinguish:\n\n- WAL shared-memory atomics (`walIndexMap`, `walFrames`, `walRead*`\n  function family, atomic / CAS primitives inside `pager.c` / `wal.c`).\n- Checkpoint cost (`sqlite3WalCheckpoint`, busy-handler interaction,\n  auto-checkpoint threshold hits).\n- Per-connection allocator behavior (`sqlite3MallocSize`,\n  `sqlite3_release_memory`, lookaside hit/miss if surfaceable).\n- Parse cost on sticky reader connections (`sqlite3RunParser`,\n  `sqlite3VdbePrepare`). Should be high if E.1 hypothesis applies\n  to F.0 topology; should be low if F.0 already amortized it.\n- Our code share (engine + worker dispatch).\n\nOutput: classification JSON + a short reviewer-ready note picking\nthe strongest single lever among G.1 / G.2 / G.3 for the next\nphase. No production code change. No commit unless the diagnostic\nadds a `#[ignore]`-gated counter test.\n\n### G.1 — Reader-worker lookaside tuning\n\nConfigure SQLite per-connection lookaside immediately after\n`Connection::open` for each F.0 reader worker. Use\n`sqlite3_db_config(SQLITE_DBCONFIG_LOOKASIDE, ...)` with\ndocumented sane defaults (per https://www.sqlite.org/malloc.html\n§3 — typical 1200-byte slots, 100 slots, sized for the workload's\nprepared-statement footprint; revise from G.0 evidence).\n\nExpected impact (per SQLite docs): ~10–15% overall perf in\nallocator-heavy workloads. Reader-side, expressed across N=8\nworkers with sticky connections, is exactly the documented happy\npath. Sequential effect: small. Concurrent effect: small-to-\nmedium if the allocator is contended.\n\nKEEP / REVERT decision rule lives in `G1-reader-lookaside.md`.\nNumeric KEEP target: any clean, reproducible improvement on\nconcurrent_median_ms with no AC-017 / AC-018 regression. Lookaside\nis too small a lever to require AC-020 closure alone — it is a\nsequencing decision, not a closer.\n\n### G.2 — Per-worker prepared-statement cache (sticky-connection revisit of E.1)\n\nE.1 (Pack 5) added `prepare_cached` on the four read-path search\nstatements against borrow/release pool connections. Sequential\nimproved -13.7%, concurrent unchanged, ratio worsened, codex BLOCK\non public surface + decision-rule mismatch + partial test. REVERTED.\n\nThe F.0 topology _is_ the natural shape for prepared-statement\ncaching: each reader worker owns one connection for its lifetime,\nso the cache amortizes across the worker's full lifetime, not just\nthe brief borrow window. G.2 re-runs that experiment with two\nbinding constraints from E.1's review:\n\n- All four statements covered (no partial test).\n- No public Rust API expansion. Use private worker-internal cache\n  with an integration test that drives observable behavior, not a\n  `pub fn ..._for_test` accessor unless it is `#[cfg(debug_assertions)]`-gated and explicitly justified in the diff.\n\nKEEP target: AC-020 numerics improve cleanly (no ratio worsening).\nThe Pack 5 §5 entry binds: G.2 is not a retry of the same\nexperiment; it is the same SQL change applied to a strictly\ndifferent connection-lifetime topology. Whitepaper §12 carries the\nexplicit override note.\n\n### G.3 — WAL checkpoint policy / tuning\n\nAdjust auto-checkpoint threshold (PRAGMA `wal_autocheckpoint`),\nbusy timeout, or move to an explicit application-driven checkpoint\nschedule on the writer side. If G.0 telemetry says checkpoint cost\nis small or zero on the read-heavy fixture, G.3 may be SKIPPED in\nthis packet and queued for a real-write-load packet.\n\nKEEP target: lower variance + lower max latency on AC-020\nconcurrent runs without regressing AC-017 / AC-018.\n\n## 5. Phase ordering\n\n1. G.0 telemetry first. Picks strongest lever or surfaces a non-\n   listed bottleneck (orchestrator pivot point).\n2. Run interventions in the order G.0 picks. Default order is\n   G.1 → G.2 → G.3.\n3. After each intervention: KEEP or REVERT, then re-measure\n   AC-020 N=5 and update the chained baseline-of-record.\n4. Final synthesis at packet close: cumulative speedup vs F.0\n   baseline (3.49×) and vs the original Pack 5 baseline (1.49×).\n\n## 6. Decision rules (per phase)\n\n- KEEP iff AC-017 + AC-018 stay green AND AC-020 numerics improve\n  cleanly (no ratio worsening, no concurrent_median_ms regression\n  outside one stddev) AND no contract / public-surface violation.\n- INCONCLUSIVE iff numerics flat within noise; record evidence and\n  move on.\n- REVERT iff any of the above fails.\n\nThe packet-close success definition is **not** \"AC-020 closes\nwithin 0.6.0\". It is \"every canonical-SQLite lever has been tried,\nKEEPs are landed, and the residual gap is documented well enough\nthat Pack 7 (WAL2 / vendor-SQLite / reader-writer split) can be\nscoped from evidence rather than guess.\"\n\n## 7. Reviewer requirements\n\nCodex `gpt-5.4` high reviewer **mandatory on KEEP / INCONCLUSIVE**\nfor G.1 / G.2 / G.3. G.0 is read-only diagnostics — reviewer\noptional unless it lands a counter test.\n\nReviewer must confirm per phase:\n\n- No retry of an §5 do-not-retry experiment without explicit\n  override note in the prompt + whitepaper.\n- No public Rust API expansion without ADR / interface-doc work,\n  or `#[cfg(debug_assertions)]` gating with the existing convention.\n- AC-018 unchanged; same-snapshot cursor contract (REQ-013 /\n  AC-059b / REQ-055) preserved.\n- `./scripts/agent-verify.sh` run after meaningful edits (not\n  `dev/agent-verify.sh` — that path does not exist, F.0 reviewer\n  block #3).\n\n## 8. Out of scope for Pack 6.G\n\n- WAL2 mode. Branch-only SQLite; Pack 7 territory.\n- `libsqlite3-sys` replacement / vendor-SQLite path. Pack 7.\n- Reader/writer physical separation. Pack 7.\n- Schema/index changes (e.g. `canonical_nodes(write_cursor)`).\n- Any change that re-opens borrow/release pooling. F.0 is the\n  load-bearing topology for the entire G-phase.\n- Public Rust API expansion. `_for_test` accessors only with\n  `#[cfg(debug_assertions)]` per F.0 reviewer convention.\n\n## 9. Failure interpretation\n\nIf G.0 + G.1 + G.2 + G.3 all land KEEP and AC-020 still does not\nclose: ship 0.6.0 with REQ-020 deferred (per the F.0 packet-close\nposition) and open Pack 7 with the cumulative G-phase evidence as\nthe input.\n\nIf telemetry instead surfaces a **new** bottleneck class (e.g. a\nspecific hot path in `vec0` that is amenable to a SQL or query-\nplan tweak), the orchestrator may add a G.4 phase by appending to\nthis handoff and the STATUS phase-results table — same review +\nTDD discipline applies.\n\n## 10. Spawning interventions\n\nUse the resume §4 spawn block with anti-chaining defenses. Per-\nphase prompts live alongside this handoff:\n\n- `dev/plan/prompts/G0-wal-checkpoint-telemetry.md`\n- `dev/plan/prompts/G1-reader-lookaside.md` (authored after G.0)\n- `dev/plan/prompts/G2-per-worker-stmt-cache.md` (authored after\n  G.0 / G.1 KEEP)\n- `dev/plan/prompts/G3-checkpoint-tuning.md` (authored after\n  G.0 / G.1 / G.2)\n\nImplementer model: Opus 4.7 high. Reviewer: codex `gpt-5.4` high.\nWorktree pattern: `/tmp/fdb-pack6G-<phase>-<ts>`. Branch:\n`pack6G-<phase>-<ts>`.\n\n## 11. Pause points\n\n- After G.0 returns. Orchestrator reviews telemetry JSON, picks\n  next-phase ordering, and pauses for human review before\n  spawning G.1.\n- After each KEEP / REVERT decision (§3 update protocol in\n  `01-orchestrator-resume.md`).\n- After packet close (cumulative-vs-F.0 + cumulative-vs-Pack-5\n  numbers in the final synthesis JSON).\n\n## Update log\n\n- 2026-05-04 — Authored from the user's \"Best next opportunities\n  on top of F.0\" briefing. G.0 telemetry first; default ordering\n  G.1 → G.2 → G.3; Pack 6 F.0 baseline `a00cd13` (seq 531 ms /\n  conc 155 ms / speedup 3.49× / N=5).\n","numLines":247,"startLine":1,"totalLines":247}}}
dev/plans/runs/G1-reader-lookaside-20260504T135138Z.log:85:{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_012Q3dsZKo1zo5H7mi8yxJKu","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t{\n2\t  \"phase\": \"G.0\",\n3\t  \"decision_self\": \"PICK_G1\",\n4\t  \"commit_sha\": \"c71f0cc167a72c8c684c27494a29ba4c80558776\",\n5\t  \"branch\": \"pack6G-G0-20260504T132839Z\",\n6\t  \"host_caveat\": \"This worktree host (5.15-tegra, schedutil, ~3x slower in absolute ms than the Pack 5 reference machine). Use share/ratio comparisons across packs, not absolute ms.\",\n7\t  \"ac017_runs\": [\n8\t    {\n9\t      \"passed\": true,\n10\t      \"profile\": \"release\",\n11\t      \"notes\": \"release-profile perf_gates run prior to perf capture: AC-017 + AC-018 ran via `cargo test --release -p fathomdb-engine --test perf_gates -- ac_017 ac_018`; AC018_NUMBERS drain_ms=51, both green.\"\n12\t    },\n13\t    {\n14\t      \"passed\": true,\n15\t      \"profile\": \"dev (agent-verify retry)\",\n16\t      \"notes\": \"First agent-verify run flaked AC-017 in dev profile at write 814 (5s deadline; slow host + dev-build write throughput). Retry passed cleanly. Treat AC-017 as green for the F.0 baseline.\"\n17\t    }\n18\t  ],\n19\t  \"ac018_runs\": [\n20\t    {\n21\t      \"drain_ms\": 51,\n22\t      \"passed\": true,\n23\t      \"notes\": \"release; AC018_NUMBERS drain_ms=51; well under the 2 s gate.\"\n24\t    }\n25\t  ],\n26\t  \"ac020_runs\": [\n27\t    {\"run\": 1, \"sequential_ms\": 542, \"concurrent_ms\": 175, \"bound_ms\": 101, \"speedup\": 3.097, \"passed_5_33x\": false, \"passed_packet_1_25_margin\": false},\n28\t    {\"run\": 2, \"sequential_ms\": 552, \"concurrent_ms\": 175, \"bound_ms\": 103, \"speedup\": 3.154, \"passed_5_33x\": false, \"passed_packet_1_25_margin\": false},\n29\t    {\"run\": 3, \"sequential_ms\": 523, \"concurrent_ms\": 143, \"bound_ms\": 98,  \"speedup\": 3.657, \"passed_5_33x\": false, \"passed_packet_1_25_margin\": false},\n30\t    {\"run\": 4, \"sequential_ms\": 558, \"concurrent_ms\": 161, \"bound_ms\": 104, \"speedup\": 3.466, \"passed_5_33x\": false, \"passed_packet_1_25_margin\": false},\n31\t    {\"run\": 5, \"sequential_ms\": 561, \"concurrent_ms\": 168, \"bound_ms\": 105, \"speedup\": 3.339, \"passed_5_33x\": false, \"passed_packet_1_25_margin\": false}\n32\t  ],\n33\t  \"ac020_summary\": {\n34\t    \"sequential_ms\": {\"min\": 523, \"median\": 552, \"max\": 561, \"stddev\": 13.73},\n35\t    \"concurrent_ms\": {\"min\": 143, \"median\": 168, \"max\": 175, \"stddev\": 11.89},\n36\t    \"speedup\":      {\"min\": 3.097, \"median\": 3.339, \"max\": 3.657, \"stddev\": 0.205}\n37\t  },\n38\t  \"baseline_of_record_for_g_phase\": {\n39\t    \"note\": \"Use this median row as the post-F.0 baseline-of-record for G.1 / G.2 / G.3 KEEP/REVERT decisions on this host. Cross-pack comparisons should use the speedup ratio, not absolute ms.\",\n40\t    \"sequential_ms_median\": 552,\n41\t    \"concurrent_ms_median\": 168,\n42\t    \"speedup_median\": 3.339,\n43\t    \"n\": 5\n44\t  },\n45\t  \"perf_record_meta\": {\n46\t    \"frequency_hz\": 999,\n47\t    \"call_graph\": \"dwarf\",\n48\t    \"event\": \"cycles:u\",\n49\t    \"perf_binary\": \"/tmp/perf-real/usr/lib/linux-tools-5.15.0-124/perf\",\n50\t    \"perf_version\": \"5.15.163\",\n51\t    \"kernel\": \"5.15.185-tegra\",\n52\t    \"perf_event_paranoid\": 2,\n53\t    \"build_command\": \"RUSTFLAGS='-C force-frame-pointers=yes' cargo build -p fathomdb-engine --release --test perf_gates\",\n54\t    \"test_binary\": \"target/release/deps/perf_gates-dc9b11b622356ab0\",\n55\t    \"sequential_phase_entry\": \"AC020_PHASE=sequential ac_020_sequential_only --ignored\",\n56\t    \"concurrent_phase_entry\": \"AC020_PHASE=concurrent ac_020_concurrent_only --ignored\",\n57\t    \"samples_seq\": 1406,\n58\t    \"samples_conc\": 1201,\n59\t    \"wall_seq_ms\": 566,\n60\t    \"wall_conc_ms\": 120\n61\t  },\n62\t  \"flamegraphs\": {\n63\t    \"sequential_data\":   \"dev/notes/perf/ac020-seq-c71f0cc.data\",\n64\t    \"concurrent_data\":   \"dev/notes/perf/ac020-conc-c71f0cc.data\",\n65\t    \"sequential_folded\": \"dev/notes/perf/ac020-seq-c71f0cc.folded\",\n66\t    \"concurrent_folded\": \"dev/notes/perf/ac020-conc-c71f0cc.folded\",\n67\t    \"sequential_svg\":    \"dev/notes/perf/ac020-seq-c71f0cc.svg\",\n68\t    \"concurrent_svg\":    \"dev/notes/perf/ac020-conc-c71f0cc.svg\"\n69\t  },\n70\t  \"classification_methodology\": {\n71\t    \"filter\": \"Restricted to samples whose stack root is the `fathomdb-reader` worker thread OR whose stack contains `run_ac020_mix`. This excludes the seed/open/close phases and isolates the measured AC-020 loop on both seq and conc captures.\",\n72\t    \"attribution\": \"Stack-aware. Atomic/mutex primitive leaves are reattributed up-stack: leaves under `sqlite3Malloc*` / `sqlite3_free` / `__libc_malloc/free` / `pcache1Alloc` etc. are classified as `allocator_lookaside`; leaves under `pcache1Fetch/Unpin/Destroy` etc. are classified as `page_cache`; leaves under WAL frames (`walIndexMap`, `walFrames`, `unixShm*`, `walRead*`, `walTryBeginRead`, `walRestartLog`, `walLockShared/Exclusive`, ...) are classified as `wal_atomics`. Only atomic/mutex primitives whose stack does NOT walk through any of those frames remain in the `mutex_atomic` catch-all.\",\n73\t    \"why_this_differs_from_a2\": \"Pack 5 A.2 used leaf-only attribution and reported `mutex_atomic = 36.98%` conc as the dominant bottleneck. Stack-aware reclassification of the same primitive samples on the F.0 tip shows nearly all of those pthread/aarch64 atomic samples are reachable from `sqlite3Malloc.part.0` -> `__GI___libc_malloc` (glibc malloc-arena mutex) or from `pcache1Fetch/Alloc` (SQLite global pcache mutex), NOT from a SQLite serialized-connection mutex. Leaf-only A.2 conflated allocator-arena contention with connection-mutex contention. F.0 collapsed the connection-mutex cost (mutex_atomic catch-all bucket is 0% conc); the residual is allocator-arena + pcache1 mutex, which is a different lever.\",\n74\t    \"filtered_total_cycles_seq\": 402434425,\n75\t    \"filtered_total_cycles_conc\": 649558353\n76\t  },\n77\t  \"symbol_classification\": [\n78\t    {\"name\": \"wal_atomics\",         \"seq_pct\": 1.04,  \"conc_pct\": 0.00,  \"ratio\": 0.00, \"delta_cycles_M\": -4.18},\n79\t    {\"name\": \"checkpoint\",          \"seq_pct\": 0.00,  \"conc_pct\": 0.00,  \"ratio\": null, \"delta_cycles_M\": 0.00},\n80\t    {\"name\": \"allocator_lookaside\", \"seq_pct\": 6.86,  \"conc_pct\": 26.67, \"ratio\": 3.89, \"delta_cycles_M\": 145.66},\n81\t    {\"name\": \"page_cache\",          \"seq_pct\": 1.57,  \"conc_pct\": 6.29,  \"ratio\": 4.01, \"delta_cycles_M\": 34.54},\n82\t    {\"name\": \"parse_compile\",       \"seq_pct\": 36.95, \"conc_pct\": 22.52, \"ratio\": 0.61, \"delta_cycles_M\": -2.39},\n83\t    {\"name\": \"vec0_fts\",            \"seq_pct\": 27.42, \"conc_pct\": 24.12, \"ratio\": 0.88, \"delta_cycles_M\": 46.34},\n84\t    {\"name\": \"our_code\",            \"seq_pct\": 24.53, \"conc_pct\": 19.78, \"ratio\": 0.81, \"delta_cycles_M\": 29.75},\n85\t    {\"name\": \"mutex_atomic\",        \"seq_pct\": 0.00,  \"conc_pct\": 0.00,  \"ratio\": null, \"delta_cycles_M\": 0.00},\n86\t    {\"name\": \"other\",               \"seq_pct\": 1.64,  \"conc_pct\": 0.61,  \"ratio\": 0.37, \"delta_cycles_M\": -2.60}\n87\t  ],\n88\t  \"leaf_only_classification_for_a2_comparison\": {\n89\t    \"note\": \"Replicates A.2's leaf-only methodology on the same captures (no filter, full profile). Provided for cross-pack continuity. Stack-aware rows above are the load-bearing classification.\",\n90\t    \"buckets\": [\n91\t      {\"name\": \"wal_atomics\",         \"seq_pct\": 1.21,  \"conc_pct\": 0.17,  \"ratio\": 0.14},\n92\t      {\"name\": \"checkpoint\",          \"seq_pct\": 0.00,  \"conc_pct\": 0.00,  \"ratio\": null},\n93\t      {\"name\": \"allocator_lookaside\", \"seq_pct\": 3.64,  \"conc_pct\": 4.53,  \"ratio\": 1.24},\n94\t      {\"name\": \"parse_compile\",       \"seq_pct\": 20.04, \"conc_pct\": 16.35, \"ratio\": 0.82},\n95\t      {\"name\": \"vec0_fts\",            \"seq_pct\": 16.44, \"conc_pct\": 12.44, \"ratio\": 0.76},\n96\t      {\"name\": \"our_code\",            \"seq_pct\": 2.34,  \"conc_pct\": 0.40,  \"ratio\": 0.17},\n97\t      {\"name\": \"mutex_atomic\",        \"seq_pct\": 8.41,  \"conc_pct\": 35.91, \"ratio\": 4.27},\n98\t      {\"name\": \"other\",               \"seq_pct\": 47.92, \"conc_pct\": 30.21, \"ratio\": 0.63}\n99\t    ],\n100\t    \"interpretation\": \"Leaf-only mutex_atomic (35.91%) on F.0 looks numerically identical to Pack 5 A.2 (36.98%). The stack-aware view above shows this is misleading: the share is now allocator-arena + pcache1 mutex, not the SQLite global serialized mutex. F.0 did move the bottleneck class even though the leaf-only number did not move.\"\n101\t  },\n102\t  \"top_concurrent_mutex_atomic_call_sites\": [\n103\t    {\"share_of_mutex_atomic_pct\": 4.78, \"context\": \"sqlite3BtreeIndexMoveto -> moveToRoot -> getAndInitPage -> getPageNormal -> pcache1Fetch -> mutex\"},\n104\t    {\"share_of_mutex_atomic_pct\": 3.76, \"context\": \"sqlite3VdbeHalt -> sqlite3VdbeFreeCursorNN -> btreeReleaseAllCursorPages -> pthread_mutex_unlock\"},\n105\t    {\"share_of_mutex_atomic_pct\": 3.55, \"context\": \"sqlite3VdbeExec -> sqlite3BtreeOpen -> sqlite3Malloc.part.0 -> pthread_mutex_unlock\"},\n106\t    {\"share_of_mutex_atomic_pct\": 3.46, \"context\": \"getAndInitPage -> getPageNormal -> pcache1Fetch -> pthread_mutex_unlock\"},\n107\t    {\"share_of_mutex_atomic_pct\": 2.97, \"context\": \"sqlite3Fts5ExprNew -> sqlite3Fts5ParseNearset -> sqlite3Malloc.part.0 -> pthread_mutex_lock\"},\n108\t    {\"share_of_mutex_atomic_pct\": 2.85, \"context\": \"sqlite3Fts5IndexQuery -> fts5SegIterNextPage -> fts5DataRead -> sqlite3Malloc.part.0\"},\n109\t    {\"share_of_mutex_atomic_pct\": 2.79, \"context\": \"sqlite3VdbeExec -> vec0Filter_knn_chunks_iter -> sqlite3_free\"},\n110\t    {\"share_of_mutex_atomic_pct\": 2.37, \"context\": \"pcache1Destroy -> sqlite3_free -> pthread_mutex_lock -> __lll_lock_wait\"},\n111\t    {\"share_of_mutex_atomic_pct\": 2.18, \"context\": \"sqlite3BtreeClose -> sqlite3_free -> pthread_mutex_lock -> __lll_lock_wait\"},\n112\t    {\"share_of_mutex_atomic_pct\": 2.03, \"context\": \"pcache1FetchStage2 -> pcache1Alloc -> sqlite3Malloc.part.0 -> pthread_mutex_unlock\"}\n113\t  ],\n114\t  \"f0_topology_holds\": true,\n115\t  \"f0_topology_holds_evidence\": \"After stack-aware reclassification, the `mutex_atomic` catch-all (atomic/mutex primitives that are NOT on allocator/pcache/wal paths) is 0.00% conc on the measured-loop filter. SQLite's serialized-connection mutex contention has been collapsed by F.0's thread-affine workers as expected. The residual concurrent-vs-sequential gap is allocator-arena and pcache1 mutex contention, plus baseline parse/vec0 work that does not scale super-linearly. The leaf-only number `mutex_atomic = 35.91%` looks unchanged from Pack 5 only because the same primitives now sit under different SQLite frames.\",\n116\t  \"recommendation\": {\n117\t    \"lever\": \"G.1\",\n118\t    \"rationale\": \"allocator_lookaside is 26.67% of conc cycles with ratio 3.89 vs sequential and a +145.7M-cycle delta (the largest absolute contention delta in the profile). The hot stacks are sqlite3DbMallocRaw / sqlite3Malloc.part.0 -> __GI___libc_malloc / __libc_free, with pthread_mutex contention on the glibc malloc arena. This is exactly the documented happy-path for SQLite's per-connection lookaside (https://www.sqlite.org/malloc.html §3): a sticky long-lived reader connection is the right amortization shape, and F.0 just made every reader connection sticky for life. Lookaside satisfies most small allocations from a per-connection arena, drops the rate of __libc_malloc calls, and removes the glibc arena mutex from the hot path. Expected impact class: medium on concurrent_median_ms (allocator pressure pattern), small on sequential. page_cache is the next-largest growth (4.01x ratio, +34.5M delta) and would be a G.4 candidate if G.1 lands cleanly but does not close.\",\n119\t    \"expected_impact_class\": \"medium\",\n120\t    \"alternate_levers_considered\": {\n121\t      \"G.2_per_worker_stmt_cache\": \"parse_compile is 22.52% conc but its ratio is 0.61 (share shrinks under concurrency; it is being displaced by contention, not driving it). G.2 reduces a CPU floor rather than removing a contention point, so it would lower seq more than conc and could worsen the speedup ratio (Pack 5 E.1 ratio-worsening risk). Defer until after G.1 settles.\",\n122\t      \"G.3_checkpoint_or_wal_tuning\": \"wal_atomics is 0.00% conc, checkpoint is 0.00% conc on this read-heavy fixture. G.3 is not warranted in this packet; queue for a write-load packet.\"\n123\t    },\n124\t    \"decision_rule_match\": \"Spec §2 G.0: 'If `allocator_lookaside > 8%` of conc cycles or shows the documented allocator pressure pattern: pick G.1 first.' We have 26.67% conc and the documented allocator-arena pressure pattern.\"\n125\t  },\n126\t  \"unexpected_observations\": [\n127\t    \"Pack 5 A.2's leaf-only `mutex_atomic = 36.98%` was conflating glibc malloc-arena mutex contention with SQLite serialized-connection mutex contention. Stack-aware re-classification on the F.0 tip shows the SQLite serialized-connection mutex contention is essentially zero (mutex_atomic catch-all = 0.00% conc) and the residual is dominated by glibc malloc-arena + SQLite pcache1 global mutex. This re-frames the alternative_hypothesis in F0-thread-affine-readers-output.json: it is NOT WAL shared-memory atomics but the per-connection allocator + global pcache that bound the F.0 speedup.\",\n128\t    \"wal_atomics is 0.00% of concurrent measured-loop cycles — the canonical-SQLite WAL shared-memory contention hypothesis is FALSIFIED for this read-only AC-020 fixture. WAL2 / vendor-SQLite work (Pack 7) cannot be motivated by WAL-atomic evidence on this fixture; it would need a write-heavy or mixed workload to justify.\",\n129\t    \"checkpoint is 0.00% — read-heavy fixture, no checkpoint pressure visible. G.3 is queued for a future write-load packet, not applicable in 6.G.\",\n130\t    \"page_cache (pcache1Fetch / Unpin / Alloc / Destroy) shows 4.01x growth (1.57% -> 6.29%, +34.5M cycles). This is a SECOND independent contention path that G.1 will partially mask (lookaside reduces pcache1Alloc fall-through to sqlite3Malloc) but not fully remove (pcache1 has its own global mutex). If G.1 KEEPs and the residual gap is still concurrent_median_ms > 100 ms, the next G.4 lever is the global page-cache mutex (PRAGMA cache_size per-connection / private cache) — but that overlaps the §3 do-not-retry list on cache_size global tuning. Note for orchestrator: a per-connection (private) page cache is a different lever from global cache_size tuning and is canonical-SQLite (PRAGMA private_cache=ON / SQLITE_OPEN_PRIVATECACHE).\",\n131\t    \"our_code = 19.78% conc when classified by full stack (any frame contains fathomdb_engine / Engine:: / read_search_in_tx / reader_worker_loop / etc). This is high because the entire SQLite stack runs UNDER our worker functions; it is not a hot spot — leaf-level our_code share is 0.32% conc, consistent with Pack 5 A.2's 0.17% leaf-only number. Reported here for transparency; the load-bearing reading is leaf-only or per-call-site.\"\n132\t  ],\n133\t  \"agent_verify_status\": \"pass\",\n134\t  \"agent_verify_reason\": \"First run flaked AC-017 in dev profile at write 814 (5 s deadline) — a known-flaky combination of slow host (5.15-tegra, schedutil, ~3x slower than Pack 5 reference) and dev-profile write throughput. Re-ran ./scripts/agent-verify.sh; second run completed with rc=0. Treat as pass for the F.0 baseline. Release-profile AC-017 + AC-018 ran clean in the perf-capture preflight (drain_ms=51).\",\n135\t  \"do_not_retry_cross_check\": [\n136\t    {\"item\": \"B.1 runtime sqlite3_config(SQLITE_CONFIG_MULTITHREAD)\",                 \"did_not_re_run\": true, \"evidence\": \"G.0 is read-only telemetry on the F.0 tip. No sqlite3_config calls were added or modified.\"},\n137\t    {\"item\": \"C.1 compile-time SQLITE_THREADSAFE=2 rebuild\",                          \"did_not_re_run\": true, \"evidence\": \"No libsqlite3-sys / build.rs changes; canonical SQLite serialized mode unchanged.\"},\n138\t    {\"item\": \"E.1 read-path prepare_cached on borrow/release pool connections\",      \"did_not_re_run\": true, \"evidence\": \"No prepare_cached changes. G.2 (sticky thread-affine prepared cache) is a future packet, not performed here.\"},\n139\t    {\"item\": \"Reader cache_size / mmap_size global tuning\",                          \"did_not_re_run\": true, \"evidence\": \"No PRAGMA cache_size / mmap_size production-default changes. G.0 only measures.\"},\n140\t    {\"item\": \"Reader open flags READ_ONLY | NO_MUTEX\",                               \"did_not_re_run\": true, \"evidence\": \"Reader connection open flags untouched.\"}\n141\t  ],\n142\t  \"code_changes\": \"none\",\n143\t  \"tests_run\": [\n144\t    \"RUSTFLAGS='-C force-frame-pointers=yes' cargo build -p fathomdb-engine --release --test perf_gates — built clean (1 pre-existing dead_code warning on F.0's worker_count/live_count helpers)\",\n145\t    \"cargo test --release -p fathomdb-engine --test perf_gates -- ac_017 ac_018 — both green; AC018 drain_ms=51\",\n146\t    \"AGENT_LONG=1 cargo test --release -p fathomdb-engine --test perf_gates ac_020_reads_do_not_serialize -- --nocapture --test-threads=1 (x5) — gate fails as documented, all numeric output captured\",\n147\t    \"AC020_PHASE=sequential perf record -F 999 -g --call-graph dwarf -- ac_020_sequential_only --ignored — 1406 samples, 11.5 MB\",\n148\t    \"AC020_PHASE=concurrent perf record -F 999 -g --call-graph dwarf -- ac_020_concurrent_only --ignored — 1201 samples, 9.8 MB\",\n149\t    \"inferno-collapse-perf + inferno-flamegraph for both seq/conc folded + svg\",\n150\t    \"./scripts/agent-verify.sh — first run flaked AC-017 in dev profile (slow host); retry rc=0 pass\"\n151\t  ],\n152\t  \"next_phase_input\": {\n153\t    \"for_orchestrator\": \"Spawn G.1 (reader-worker lookaside tuning) implementer prompt next. Carry these numbers as the post-F.0 baseline-of-record on this host: seq_median=552 ms, conc_median=168 ms, speedup_median=3.339x (N=5). KEEP target per handoff §4 G.1 row: any clean, reproducible improvement on concurrent_median_ms with no AC-017 / AC-018 regression. Strongest single-experiment lookaside candidate from the SQLite docs (https://www.sqlite.org/malloc.html §3) for a sticky reader-connection footprint: sqlite3_db_config(SQLITE_DBCONFIG_LOOKASIDE, NULL, slot_size, slot_count) with slot_size 1200 bytes and slot_count 500 (5x the SQLite default 128 to absorb sqlite3Fts5ExprNew + vec0Filter_knn allocations visible in the top-call-site table). The G.1 implementer should size from evidence — if the prompt author wants a cheap sweep, [128, 250, 500, 1000] x slot_size {512, 1200} is the canonical grid.\",\n154\t    \"for_packet_close\": \"If G.1 KEEPs but residual gap remains, the next-priority lever is page_cache (pcache1 global mutex) via private cache mode, not G.2 or G.3.\"\n155\t  }\n156\t}\n157\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"14d083b7-460f-4635-b7a8-5e1b3e7e8a72","uuid":"24630fa7-4be1-429f-8953-76fe12f849cd","timestamp":"2026-05-04T13:52:05.425Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/tmp/fdb-pack6G-G1-20260504T135138Z/dev/plan/runs/G0-wal-checkpoint-telemetry-output.json","content":"{\n  \"phase\": \"G.0\",\n  \"decision_self\": \"PICK_G1\",\n  \"commit_sha\": \"c71f0cc167a72c8c684c27494a29ba4c80558776\",\n  \"branch\": \"pack6G-G0-20260504T132839Z\",\n  \"host_caveat\": \"This worktree host (5.15-tegra, schedutil, ~3x slower in absolute ms than the Pack 5 reference machine). Use share/ratio comparisons across packs, not absolute ms.\",\n  \"ac017_runs\": [\n    {\n      \"passed\": true,\n      \"profile\": \"release\",\n      \"notes\": \"release-profile perf_gates run prior to perf capture: AC-017 + AC-018 ran via `cargo test --release -p fathomdb-engine --test perf_gates -- ac_017 ac_018`; AC018_NUMBERS drain_ms=51, both green.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"passed\": true,\n      \"profile\": \"dev (agent-verify retry)\",\n      \"notes\": \"First agent-verify run flaked AC-017 in dev profile at write 814 (5s deadline; slow host + dev-build write throughput). Retry passed cleanly. Treat AC-017 as green for the F.0 baseline.\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"ac018_runs\": [\n    {\n      \"drain_ms\": 51,\n      \"passed\": true,\n      \"notes\": \"release; AC018_NUMBERS drain_ms=51; well under the 2 s gate.\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"ac020_runs\": [\n    {\"run\": 1, \"sequential_ms\": 542, \"concurrent_ms\": 175, \"bound_ms\": 101, \"speedup\": 3.097, \"passed_5_33x\": false, \"passed_packet_1_25_margin\": false},\n    {\"run\": 2, \"sequential_ms\": 552, \"concurrent_ms\": 175, \"bound_ms\": 103, \"speedup\": 3.154, \"passed_5_33x\": false, \"passed_packet_1_25_margin\": false},\n    {\"run\": 3, \"sequential_ms\": 523, \"concurrent_ms\": 143, \"bound_ms\": 98,  \"speedup\": 3.657, \"passed_5_33x\": false, \"passed_packet_1_25_margin\": false},\n    {\"run\": 4, \"sequential_ms\": 558, \"concurrent_ms\": 161, \"bound_ms\": 104, \"speedup\": 3.466, \"passed_5_33x\": false, \"passed_packet_1_25_margin\": false},\n    {\"run\": 5, \"sequential_ms\": 561, \"concurrent_ms\": 168, \"bound_ms\": 105, \"speedup\": 3.339, \"passed_5_33x\": false, \"passed_packet_1_25_margin\": false}\n  ],\n  \"ac020_summary\": {\n    \"sequential_ms\": {\"min\": 523, \"median\": 552, \"max\": 561, \"stddev\": 13.73},\n    \"concurrent_ms\": {\"min\": 143, \"median\": 168, \"max\": 175, \"stddev\": 11.89},\n    \"speedup\":      {\"min\": 3.097, \"median\": 3.339, \"max\": 3.657, \"stddev\": 0.205}\n  },\n  \"baseline_of_record_for_g_phase\": {\n    \"note\": \"Use this median row as the post-F.0 baseline-of-record for G.1 / G.2 / G.3 KEEP/REVERT decisions on this host. Cross-pack comparisons should use the speedup ratio, not absolute ms.\",\n    \"sequential_ms_median\": 552,\n    \"concurrent_ms_median\": 168,\n    \"speedup_median\": 3.339,\n    \"n\": 5\n  },\n  \"perf_record_meta\": {\n    \"frequency_hz\": 999,\n    \"call_graph\": \"dwarf\",\n    \"event\": \"cycles:u\",\n    \"perf_binary\": \"/tmp/perf-real/usr/lib/linux-tools-5.15.0-124/perf\",\n    \"perf_version\": \"5.15.163\",\n    \"kernel\": \"5.15.185-tegra\",\n    \"perf_event_paranoid\": 2,\n    \"build_command\": \"RUSTFLAGS='-C force-frame-pointers=yes' cargo build -p fathomdb-engine --release --test perf_gates\",\n    \"test_binary\": \"target/release/deps/perf_gates-dc9b11b622356ab0\",\n    \"sequential_phase_entry\": \"AC020_PHASE=sequential ac_020_sequential_only --ignored\",\n    \"concurrent_phase_entry\": \"AC020_PHASE=concurrent ac_020_concurrent_only --ignored\",\n    \"samples_seq\": 1406,\n    \"samples_conc\": 1201,\n    \"wall_seq_ms\": 566,\n    \"wall_conc_ms\": 120\n  },\n  \"flamegraphs\": {\n    \"sequential_data\":   \"dev/notes/perf/ac020-seq-c71f0cc.data\",\n    \"concurrent_data\":   \"dev/notes/perf/ac020-conc-c71f0cc.data\",\n    \"sequential_folded\": \"dev/notes/perf/ac020-seq-c71f0cc.folded\",\n    \"concurrent_folded\": \"dev/notes/perf/ac020-conc-c71f0cc.folded\",\n    \"sequential_svg\":    \"dev/notes/perf/ac020-seq-c71f0cc.svg\",\n    \"concurrent_svg\":    \"dev/notes/perf/ac020-conc-c71f0cc.svg\"\n  },\n  \"classification_methodology\": {\n    \"filter\": \"Restricted to samples whose stack root is the `fathomdb-reader` worker thread OR whose stack contains `run_ac020_mix`. This excludes the seed/open/close phases and isolates the measured AC-020 loop on both seq and conc captures.\",\n    \"attribution\": \"Stack-aware. Atomic/mutex primitive leaves are reattributed up-stack: leaves under `sqlite3Malloc*` / `sqlite3_free` / `__libc_malloc/free` / `pcache1Alloc` etc. are classified as `allocator_lookaside`; leaves under `pcache1Fetch/Unpin/Destroy` etc. are classified as `page_cache`; leaves under WAL frames (`walIndexMap`, `walFrames`, `unixShm*`, `walRead*`, `walTryBeginRead`, `walRestartLog`, `walLockShared/Exclusive`, ...) are classified as `wal_atomics`. Only atomic/mutex primitives whose stack does NOT walk through any of those frames remain in the `mutex_atomic` catch-all.\",\n    \"why_this_differs_from_a2\": \"Pack 5 A.2 used leaf-only attribution and reported `mutex_atomic = 36.98%` conc as the dominant bottleneck. Stack-aware reclassification of the same primitive samples on the F.0 tip shows nearly all of those pthread/aarch64 atomic samples are reachable from `sqlite3Malloc.part.0` -> `__GI___libc_malloc` (glibc malloc-arena mutex) or from `pcache1Fetch/Alloc` (SQLite global pcache mutex), NOT from a SQLite serialized-connection mutex. Leaf-only A.2 conflated allocator-arena contention with connection-mutex contention. F.0 collapsed the connection-mutex cost (mutex_atomic catch-all bucket is 0% conc); the residual is allocator-arena + pcache1 mutex, which is a different lever.\",\n    \"filtered_total_cycles_seq\": 402434425,\n    \"filtered_total_cycles_conc\": 649558353\n  },\n  \"symbol_classification\": [\n    {\"name\": \"wal_atomics\",         \"seq_pct\": 1.04,  \"conc_pct\": 0.00,  \"ratio\": 0.00, \"delta_cycles_M\": -4.18},\n    {\"name\": \"checkpoint\",          \"seq_pct\": 0.00,  \"conc_pct\": 0.00,  \"ratio\": null, \"delta_cycles_M\": 0.00},\n    {\"name\": \"allocator_lookaside\", \"seq_pct\": 6.86,  \"conc_pct\": 26.67, \"ratio\": 3.89, \"delta_cycles_M\": 145.66},\n    {\"name\": \"page_cache\",          \"seq_pct\": 1.57,  \"conc_pct\": 6.29,  \"ratio\": 4.01, \"delta_cycles_M\": 34.54},\n    {\"name\": \"parse_compile\",       \"seq_pct\": 36.95, \"conc_pct\": 22.52, \"ratio\": 0.61, \"delta_cycles_M\": -2.39},\n    {\"name\": \"vec0_fts\",            \"seq_pct\": 27.42, \"conc_pct\": 24.12, \"ratio\": 0.88, \"delta_cycles_M\": 46.34},\n    {\"name\": \"our_code\",            \"seq_pct\": 24.53, \"conc_pct\": 19.78, \"ratio\": 0.81, \"delta_cycles_M\": 29.75},\n    {\"name\": \"mutex_atomic\",        \"seq_pct\": 0.00,  \"conc_pct\": 0.00,  \"ratio\": null, \"delta_cycles_M\": 0.00},\n    {\"name\": \"other\",               \"seq_pct\": 1.64,  \"conc_pct\": 0.61,  \"ratio\": 0.37, \"delta_cycles_M\": -2.60}\n  ],\n  \"leaf_only_classification_for_a2_comparison\": {\n    \"note\": \"Replicates A.2's leaf-only methodology on the same captures (no filter, full profile). Provided for cross-pack continuity. Stack-aware rows above are the load-bearing classification.\",\n    \"buckets\": [\n      {\"name\": \"wal_atomics\",         \"seq_pct\": 1.21,  \"conc_pct\": 0.17,  \"ratio\": 0.14},\n      {\"name\": \"checkpoint\",          \"seq_pct\": 0.00,  \"conc_pct\": 0.00,  \"ratio\": null},\n      {\"name\": \"allocator_lookaside\", \"seq_pct\": 3.64,  \"conc_pct\": 4.53,  \"ratio\": 1.24},\n      {\"name\": \"parse_compile\",       \"seq_pct\": 20.04, \"conc_pct\": 16.35, \"ratio\": 0.82},\n      {\"name\": \"vec0_fts\",            \"seq_pct\": 16.44, \"conc_pct\": 12.44, \"ratio\": 0.76},\n      {\"name\": \"our_code\",            \"seq_pct\": 2.34,  \"conc_pct\": 0.40,  \"ratio\": 0.17},\n      {\"name\": \"mutex_atomic\",        \"seq_pct\": 8.41,  \"conc_pct\": 35.91, \"ratio\": 4.27},\n      {\"name\": \"other\",               \"seq_pct\": 47.92, \"conc_pct\": 30.21, \"ratio\": 0.63}\n    ],\n    \"interpretation\": \"Leaf-only mutex_atomic (35.91%) on F.0 looks numerically identical to Pack 5 A.2 (36.98%). The stack-aware view above shows this is misleading: the share is now allocator-arena + pcache1 mutex, not the SQLite global serialized mutex. F.0 did move the bottleneck class even though the leaf-only number did not move.\"\n  },\n  \"top_concurrent_mutex_atomic_call_sites\": [\n    {\"share_of_mutex_atomic_pct\": 4.78, \"context\": \"sqlite3BtreeIndexMoveto -> moveToRoot -> getAndInitPage -> getPageNormal -> pcache1Fetch -> mutex\"},\n    {\"share_of_mutex_atomic_pct\": 3.76, \"context\": \"sqlite3VdbeHalt -> sqlite3VdbeFreeCursorNN -> btreeReleaseAllCursorPages -> pthread_mutex_unlock\"},\n    {\"share_of_mutex_atomic_pct\": 3.55, \"context\": \"sqlite3VdbeExec -> sqlite3BtreeOpen -> sqlite3Malloc.part.0 -> pthread_mutex_unlock\"},\n    {\"share_of_mutex_atomic_pct\": 3.46, \"context\": \"getAndInitPage -> getPageNormal -> pcache1Fetch -> pthread_mutex_unlock\"},\n    {\"share_of_mutex_atomic_pct\": 2.97, \"context\": \"sqlite3Fts5ExprNew -> sqlite3Fts5ParseNearset -> sqlite3Malloc.part.0 -> pthread_mutex_lock\"},\n    {\"share_of_mutex_atomic_pct\": 2.85, \"context\": \"sqlite3Fts5IndexQuery -> fts5SegIterNextPage -> fts5DataRead -> sqlite3Malloc.part.0\"},\n    {\"share_of_mutex_atomic_pct\": 2.79, \"context\": \"sqlite3VdbeExec -> vec0Filter_knn_chunks_iter -> sqlite3_free\"},\n    {\"share_of_mutex_atomic_pct\": 2.37, \"context\": \"pcache1Destroy -> sqlite3_free -> pthread_mutex_lock -> __lll_lock_wait\"},\n    {\"share_of_mutex_atomic_pct\": 2.18, \"context\": \"sqlite3BtreeClose -> sqlite3_free -> pthread_mutex_lock -> __lll_lock_wait\"},\n    {\"share_of_mutex_atomic_pct\": 2.03, \"context\": \"pcache1FetchStage2 -> pcache1Alloc -> sqlite3Malloc.part.0 -> pthread_mutex_unlock\"}\n  ],\n  \"f0_topology_holds\": true,\n  \"f0_topology_holds_evidence\": \"After stack-aware reclassification, the `mutex_atomic` catch-all (atomic/mutex primitives that are NOT on allocator/pcache/wal paths) is 0.00% conc on the measured-loop filter. SQLite's serialized-connection mutex contention has been collapsed by F.0's thread-affine workers as expected. The residual concurrent-vs-sequential gap is allocator-arena and pcache1 mutex contention, plus baseline parse/vec0 work that does not scale super-linearly. The leaf-only number `mutex_atomic = 35.91%` looks unchanged from Pack 5 only because the same primitives now sit under different SQLite frames.\",\n  \"recommendation\": {\n    \"lever\": \"G.1\",\n    \"rationale\": \"allocator_lookaside is 26.67% of conc cycles with ratio 3.89 vs sequential and a +145.7M-cycle delta (the largest absolute contention delta in the profile). The hot stacks are sqlite3DbMallocRaw / sqlite3Malloc.part.0 -> __GI___libc_malloc / __libc_free, with pthread_mutex contention on the glibc malloc arena. This is exactly the documented happy-path for SQLite's per-connection lookaside (https://www.sqlite.org/malloc.html §3): a sticky long-lived reader connection is the right amortization shape, and F.0 just made every reader connection sticky for life. Lookaside satisfies most small allocations from a per-connection arena, drops the rate of __libc_malloc calls, and removes the glibc arena mutex from the hot path. Expected impact class: medium on concurrent_median_ms (allocator pressure pattern), small on sequential. page_cache is the next-largest growth (4.01x ratio, +34.5M delta) and would be a G.4 candidate if G.1 lands cleanly but does not close.\",\n    \"expected_impact_class\": \"medium\",\n    \"alternate_levers_considered\": {\n      \"G.2_per_worker_stmt_cache\": \"parse_compile is 22.52% conc but its ratio is 0.61 (share shrinks under concurrency; it is being displaced by contention, not driving it). G.2 reduces a CPU floor rather than removing a contention point, so it would lower seq more than conc and could worsen the speedup ratio (Pack 5 E.1 ratio-worsening risk). Defer until after G.1 settles.\",\n      \"G.3_checkpoint_or_wal_tuning\": \"wal_atomics is 0.00% conc, checkpoint is 0.00% conc on this read-heavy fixture. G.3 is not warranted in this packet; queue for a write-load packet.\"\n    },\n    \"decision_rule_match\": \"Spec §2 G.0: 'If `allocator_lookaside > 8%` of conc cycles or shows the documented allocator pressure pattern: pick G.1 first.' We have 26.67% conc and the documented allocator-arena pressure pattern.\"\n  },\n  \"unexpected_observations\": [\n    \"Pack 5 A.2's leaf-only `mutex_atomic = 36.98%` was conflating glibc malloc-arena mutex contention with SQLite serialized-connection mutex contention. Stack-aware re-classification on the F.0 tip shows the SQLite serialized-connection mutex contention is essentially zero (mutex_atomic catch-all = 0.00% conc) and the residual is dominated by glibc malloc-arena + SQLite pcache1 global mutex. This re-frames the alternative_hypothesis in F0-thread-affine-readers-output.json: it is NOT WAL shared-memory atomics but the per-connection allocator + global pcache that bound the F.0 speedup.\",\n    \"wal_atomics is 0.00% of concurrent measured-loop cycles — the canonical-SQLite WAL shared-memory contention hypothesis is FALSIFIED for this read-only AC-020 fixture. WAL2 / vendor-SQLite work (Pack 7) cannot be motivated by WAL-atomic evidence on this fixture; it would need a write-heavy or mixed workload to justify.\",\n    \"checkpoint is 0.00% — read-heavy fixture, no checkpoint pressure visible. G.3 is queued for a future write-load packet, not applicable in 6.G.\",\n    \"page_cache (pcache1Fetch / Unpin / Alloc / Destroy) shows 4.01x growth (1.57% -> 6.29%, +34.5M cycles). This is a SECOND independent contention path that G.1 will partially mask (lookaside reduces pcache1Alloc fall-through to sqlite3Malloc) but not fully remove (pcache1 has its own global mutex). If G.1 KEEPs and the residual gap is still concurrent_median_ms > 100 ms, the next G.4 lever is the global page-cache mutex (PRAGMA cache_size per-connection / private cache) — but that overlaps the §3 do-not-retry list on cache_size global tuning. Note for orchestrator: a per-connection (private) page cache is a different lever from global cache_size tuning and is canonical-SQLite (PRAGMA private_cache=ON / SQLITE_OPEN_PRIVATECACHE).\",\n    \"our_code = 19.78% conc when classified by full stack (any frame contains fathomdb_engine / Engine:: / read_search_in_tx / reader_worker_loop / etc). This is high because the entire SQLite stack runs UNDER our worker functions; it is not a hot spot — leaf-level our_code share is 0.32% conc, consistent with Pack 5 A.2's 0.17% leaf-only number. Reported here for transparency; the load-bearing reading is leaf-only or per-call-site.\"\n  ],\n  \"agent_verify_status\": \"pass\",\n  \"agent_verify_reason\": \"First run flaked AC-017 in dev profile at write 814 (5 s deadline) — a known-flaky combination of slow host (5.15-tegra, schedutil, ~3x slower than Pack 5 reference) and dev-profile write throughput. Re-ran ./scripts/agent-verify.sh; second run completed with rc=0. Treat as pass for the F.0 baseline. Release-profile AC-017 + AC-018 ran clean in the perf-capture preflight (drain_ms=51).\",\n  \"do_not_retry_cross_check\": [\n    {\"item\": \"B.1 runtime sqlite3_config(SQLITE_CONFIG_MULTITHREAD)\",                 \"did_not_re_run\": true, \"evidence\": \"G.0 is read-only telemetry on the F.0 tip. No sqlite3_config calls were added or modified.\"},\n    {\"item\": \"C.1 compile-time SQLITE_THREADSAFE=2 rebuild\",                          \"did_not_re_run\": true, \"evidence\": \"No libsqlite3-sys / build.rs changes; canonical SQLite serialized mode unchanged.\"},\n    {\"item\": \"E.1 read-path prepare_cached on borrow/release pool connections\",      \"did_not_re_run\": true, \"evidence\": \"No prepare_cached changes. G.2 (sticky thread-affine prepared cache) is a future packet, not performed here.\"},\n    {\"item\": \"Reader cache_size / mmap_size global tuning\",                          \"did_not_re_run\": true, \"evidence\": \"No PRAGMA cache_size / mmap_size production-default changes. G.0 only measures.\"},\n    {\"item\": \"Reader open flags READ_ONLY | NO_MUTEX\",                               \"did_not_re_run\": true, \"evidence\": \"Reader connection open flags untouched.\"}\n  ],\n  \"code_changes\": \"none\",\n  \"tests_run\": [\n    \"RUSTFLAGS='-C force-frame-pointers=yes' cargo build -p fathomdb-engine --release --test perf_gates — built clean (1 pre-existing dead_code warning on F.0's worker_count/live_count helpers)\",\n    \"cargo test --release -p fathomdb-engine --test perf_gates -- ac_017 ac_018 — both green; AC018 drain_ms=51\",\n    \"AGENT_LONG=1 cargo test --release -p fathomdb-engine --test perf_gates ac_020_reads_do_not_serialize -- --nocapture --test-threads=1 (x5) — gate fails as documented, all numeric output captured\",\n    \"AC020_PHASE=sequential perf record -F 999 -g --call-graph dwarf -- ac_020_sequential_only --ignored — 1406 samples, 11.5 MB\",\n    \"AC020_PHASE=concurrent perf record -F 999 -g --call-graph dwarf -- ac_020_concurrent_only --ignored — 1201 samples, 9.8 MB\",\n    \"inferno-collapse-perf + inferno-flamegraph for both seq/conc folded + svg\",\n    \"./scripts/agent-verify.sh — first run flaked AC-017 in dev profile (slow host); retry rc=0 pass\"\n  ],\n  \"next_phase_input\": {\n    \"for_orchestrator\": \"Spawn G.1 (reader-worker lookaside tuning) implementer prompt next. Carry these numbers as the post-F.0 baseline-of-record on this host: seq_median=552 ms, conc_median=168 ms, speedup_median=3.339x (N=5). KEEP target per handoff §4 G.1 row: any clean, reproducible improvement on concurrent_median_ms with no AC-017 / AC-018 regression. Strongest single-experiment lookaside candidate from the SQLite docs (https://www.sqlite.org/malloc.html §3) for a sticky reader-connection footprint: sqlite3_db_config(SQLITE_DBCONFIG_LOOKASIDE, NULL, slot_size, slot_count) with slot_size 1200 bytes and slot_count 500 (5x the SQLite default 128 to absorb sqlite3Fts5ExprNew + vec0Filter_knn allocations visible in the top-call-site table). The G.1 implementer should size from evidence — if the prompt author wants a cheap sweep, [128, 250, 500, 1000] x slot_size {512, 1200} is the canonical grid.\",\n    \"for_packet_close\": \"If G.1 KEEPs but residual gap remains, the next-priority lever is page_cache (pcache1 global mutex) via private cache mode, not G.2 or G.3.\"\n  }\n}\n","numLines":157,"startLine":1,"totalLines":157}}}
