dev/plans/runs/G1-reader-lookaside-20260504T135138Z.log:6152:{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-7","id":"msg_01DrfkHMS3wys4z9j9aAqRdZ","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_0161ErDGCTkLBpycP3FrPszh","name":"Bash","input":{"command":"git commit -m \"$(cat <<'EOF'\nperf(G1): per-reader-connection SQLite lookaside (1200B x 500 slots)\n\nPack 6.G G.1. G.0 telemetry classified `allocator_lookaside` as 26.67%\nof concurrent AC-020 cycles with a 3.89x ratio vs sequential and\n+145.7M-cycle delta — the dominant residual on the F.0 thread-affine\nreader topology. The hot stacks bottom out in `sqlite3DbMallocRaw` ->\n`__GI___libc_malloc` with pthread_mutex contention on the glibc malloc\narena (sqlite3Fts5ExprNew, vec0Filter_knn).\n\n`sqlite3_db_config(SQLITE_DBCONFIG_LOOKASIDE, NULL, 1200, 500)` runs on\neach F.0 reader worker connection immediately after `Connection::open`\nand BEFORE any PRAGMA / prepare; per the SQLite docs the call is\nsilently ignored once any allocation has occurred on the connection,\nso a `debug_assert_eq!(rc, SQLITE_OK)` guards reordering regressions.\n1200-byte slots cover the small-allocation footprint visible in the\nG.0 top-call-site table; 500 slots (5x the SQLite default 128) is\nsized for a sticky long-lived worker connection.\n\nrusqlite 0.31's `set_db_config` only handles boolean DbConfig\nvariants; `SQLITE_DBCONFIG_LOOKASIDE` is commented out in\nrusqlite/src/config.rs, so the call is via the raw FFI variadic\n`rusqlite::ffi::sqlite3_db_config`. `c_int` is used for the FFI\ninteger args per the cross-platform-rust memory; no hardcoded i8/u8.\n\nTwo debug-only test accessors (`#[cfg(debug_assertions)]` +\n`#[doc(hidden)]`, F.0 reviewer convention) drive the integration\ntests:\n  - `reader_lookaside_config_rcs_for_test` returns the rc captured at\n    open time per worker, asserting SQLITE_OK ordering.\n  - `reader_lookaside_used_per_worker_for_test` broadcasts a\n    `LookasideStatus` request to every worker (debug-only\n    ReaderRequest variant) and reads\n    `SQLITE_DBSTATUS_LOOKASIDE_USED` hiwtr per connection. Hiwtr,\n    not current, because `current` decays as transactions finalize.\n\nAC-017 + AC-018 green (drain_ms=95). agent-verify rc=0. AC-020 N=5\n(seq median 563 / conc median 161 / speedup median 3.530) is a\n~7 ms / ~0.19x improvement on the G.0 baseline (552/168/3.339,\nconc stddev 11.89). The improvement does not clear the 1xstddev\nKEEP threshold from the handoff §6 decision rule, so the\nimplementer self-decision is INCONCLUSIVE per the spec; evidence\ncaptured for the orchestrator + codex reviewer.\n\nHard rules upheld: no AC-020 bound formula change; same-snapshot\ncursor contract preserved; AC-018 still green at this commit; no\npublic Rust API expansion; no §5 do-not-retry experiment touched.\nEOF\n)\"","description":"commit"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":262,"cache_read_input_tokens":108609,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":262},"output_tokens":72,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"14d083b7-460f-4635-b7a8-5e1b3e7e8a72","uuid":"5ef736e2-5081-4e2d-b830-53c738e74efc"}
dev/plans/runs/G1-reader-lookaside-20260504T135138Z.log:8569:{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-7","id":"msg_01L2AtMJiv1zhDUr18vWsg7F","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_0142Z3mmJuacKu8YTHcGaAW3","name":"Write","input":{"file_path":"/home/coreyt/projects/fathomdb/dev/plan/runs/G1-reader-lookaside-output.json","content":"{\n  \"phase\": \"G.1\",\n  \"decision_self\": \"INCONCLUSIVE\",\n  \"decision_self_rationale\": \"AC-017 + AC-018 stayed green. Concurrent_median improved 168 ms -> 161 ms (-7 ms, ~4.2%) and speedup_median improved 3.339x -> 3.530x (+0.191x, no ratio worsening). Per handoff §6 / §8 the KEEP threshold is `concurrent_median < baseline - 1*stddev` = 168 - 11.89 = 156.11 ms; observed 161 ms misses the threshold by 4.89 ms (less than half a stddev). Movement is in the right direction but inside the noise band, so the implementer self-decision is INCONCLUSIVE. Lookaside-applied evidence captured below for the orchestrator + codex `gpt-5.4` high reviewer to confirm KEEP-or-REVERT.\",\n  \"commit_sha\": \"46e3576ba92047b68d1a8c8163e580e065871d8d\",\n  \"branch\": \"pack6G-G1-20260504T135138Z\",\n  \"host_caveat\": \"Same worktree host as G.0 (Linux 5.15-tegra, schedutil, ~3x slower than the Pack 5 reference machine). Cross-pack comparisons should use ratios, not absolute ms.\",\n  \"red_tests_written\": [\n    {\n      \"name\": \"reader_workers_have_lookaside_configured_with_ok_rc\",\n      \"file\": \"src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/tests/reader_pool.rs\",\n      \"red_failure_mode\": \"Compile-time: method `reader_lookaside_config_rcs_for_test` does not exist on `fathomdb_engine::Engine` (E0599). Pre-implementation. Asserts the rc of `sqlite3_db_config(LOOKASIDE)` captured at open time is SQLITE_OK (0) for every reader worker.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"name\": \"reader_workers_consume_lookaside_slots_after_warmup_read\",\n      \"file\": \"src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/tests/reader_pool.rs\",\n      \"red_failure_mode\": \"Compile-time: method `reader_lookaside_used_per_worker_for_test` does not exist on `fathomdb_engine::Engine` (E0599). Pre-implementation. Once compiling, this test would also fail at runtime if lookaside were misconfigured (e.g. ordered after a PRAGMA so SQLite silently ignored it) because `SQLITE_DBSTATUS_LOOKASIDE_USED` hiwtr would remain 0 after warmup. Initially also failed at runtime when the test read `current` instead of `hiwtr` (slots returned to the pool when the search transaction closed) — fixed by asserting on hiwtr, which is the right semantic for 'at least one slot was honored at any point'.\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"lookaside_config\": {\n    \"slot_size_bytes\": 1200,\n    \"slot_count\": 500,\n    \"applied_via\": \"raw FFI: rusqlite::ffi::sqlite3_db_config(handle, ffi::SQLITE_DBCONFIG_LOOKASIDE, NULL, 1200, 500). rusqlite 0.31's safe `set_db_config` wrapper only supports the boolean DbConfig::* variants; `SQLITE_DBCONFIG_LOOKASIDE` is explicitly commented out in `rusqlite-0.31.0/src/config.rs`. Used the named symbol `ffi::SQLITE_DBCONFIG_LOOKASIDE` (= 1001) rather than a magic number per cross-platform Rust convention.\",\n    \"ordering_assertion_rc\": \"0 (SQLITE_OK) for every reader worker, captured at open time before any PRAGMA / prepare ran on the connection. Captured per-worker into `Engine::reader_lookaside_rcs: Vec<i32>` (allow(dead_code) in release; read by `reader_lookaside_config_rcs_for_test` in debug).\"\n  },\n  \"lookaside_used_evidence\": {\n    \"method\": \"Debug-only `ReaderRequest::LookasideStatus` request broadcast to every worker (not round-robin); each worker calls `sqlite3_db_status(SQLITE_DBSTATUS_LOOKASIDE_USED)` and returns the high-water-mark out-param. `current` was tried first but decays as transactions finalize so it is unreliable for post-warmup evidence; `hiwtr` is the correct latched signal that lookaside was honored at any point.\",\n    \"after_warmup_test_workload\": \"READER_POOL_SIZE * 8 = 64 dispatched `engine.search('warmup')` calls (each routed round-robin to one of the 8 workers) on a fresh empty engine, search() returns Err but still parses + prepares + steps which exercises the lookaside arena.\",\n    \"hiwtr_per_worker\": [57, 57, 57, 57, 57, 57, 57, 57],\n    \"interpretation\": \"Every worker has hiwtr=57 slots used (well below the configured 500-slot capacity, ~11%). Uniformity across workers reflects the round-robin dispatch + the fact that `engine.search('warmup')` exercises the same transaction shape on each. AC-020's hybrid retrieval workload is more allocation-heavy and would push hiwtr higher; the test gate is 'consumed > 0', not 'saturated'.\"\n  },\n  \"ac017_runs\": [\n    {\n      \"passed\": true,\n      \"profile\": \"release\",\n      \"notes\": \"Run via `cargo test --release -p fathomdb-engine --test perf_gates -- ac_017 ac_018 --nocapture`; `test ac_017_vector_projection_freshness_p99_le_five_seconds ... ok` in 14.64 s wall.\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"ac018_runs\": [\n    {\n      \"drain_ms\": 95,\n      \"passed\": true,\n      \"notes\": \"release; AC018_NUMBERS drain_ms=95; well under the 2 s gate. Slightly higher than G.0's 51 ms (run-to-run; G.0 itself reported 56 ms in F.0 baseline).\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"ac020_runs\": [\n    {\"run\": 1, \"sequential_ms\": 582, \"concurrent_ms\": 153, \"bound_ms\": 109, \"speedup\": 3.804, \"passed_5_33x\": false, \"passed_packet_1_25_margin\": false},\n    {\"run\": 2, \"sequential_ms\": 547, \"concurrent_ms\": 161, \"bound_ms\": 102, \"speedup\": 3.398, \"passed_5_33x\": false, \"passed_packet_1_25_margin\": false},\n    {\"run\": 3, \"sequential_ms\": 593, \"concurrent_ms\": 168, \"bound_ms\": 111, \"speedup\": 3.530, \"passed_5_33x\": false, \"passed_packet_1_25_margin\": false},\n    {\"run\": 4, \"sequential_ms\": 563, \"concurrent_ms\": 181, \"bound_ms\": 105, \"speedup\": 3.110, \"passed_5_33x\": false, \"passed_packet_1_25_margin\": false},\n    {\"run\": 5, \"sequential_ms\": 503, \"concurrent_ms\": 118, \"bound_ms\": 94,  \"speedup\": 4.263, \"passed_5_33x\": false, \"passed_packet_1_25_margin\": false}\n  ],\n  \"ac020_summary\": {\n    \"sequential_ms\": {\"min\": 503, \"median\": 563, \"max\": 593, \"stddev\": 33.40},\n    \"concurrent_ms\": {\"min\": 118, \"median\": 161, \"max\": 181, \"stddev\": 22.83},\n    \"speedup\":      {\"min\": 3.110, \"median\": 3.530, \"max\": 4.263, \"stddev\": 0.428}\n  },\n  \"comparison_to_g0_baseline\": {\n    \"g0_baseline_of_record\": {\n      \"sequential_ms_median\": 552,\n      \"concurrent_ms_median\": 168,\n      \"speedup_median\": 3.339,\n      \"concurrent_ms_stddev\": 11.89,\n      \"n\": 5\n    },\n    \"g1_observed\": {\n      \"sequential_ms_median\": 563,\n      \"concurrent_ms_median\": 161,\n      \"speedup_median\": 3.530,\n      \"concurrent_ms_stddev\": 22.83,\n      \"n\": 5\n    },\n    \"deltas\": {\n      \"sequential_ms_median_delta\": \"+11 ms (+2.0%) — within run-to-run noise\",\n      \"concurrent_ms_median_delta\": \"-7 ms (-4.2%) — improvement, but inside G.0's 1*stddev band (11.89 ms)\",\n      \"speedup_median_delta\": \"+0.191x (+5.7%) — no ratio worsening\",\n      \"concurrent_ms_stddev_delta\": \"+10.94 ms — G.1 run shows higher variance, partly driven by run 5 (118 ms) and run 4 (181 ms); not a regression but a wider band that loosens the KEEP threshold further on this sample\"\n    },\n    \"keep_threshold_evaluation\": {\n      \"rule\": \"concurrent_median < g0_baseline.concurrent_median - 1 * g0_baseline.stddev\",\n      \"threshold_ms\": 156.11,\n      \"observed_ms\": 161,\n      \"verdict\": \"miss by 4.89 ms (~0.41 * stddev); does NOT meet KEEP threshold\",\n      \"ratio_floor_evaluation\": {\n        \"rule\": \"speedup_median >= g0_baseline.speedup_median\",\n        \"threshold\": 3.339,\n        \"observed\": 3.530,\n        \"verdict\": \"pass; no ratio worsening\"\n      }\n    }\n  },\n  \"optional_sweep_results\": null,\n  \"optional_sweep_notes\": \"Did not run the [128, 250, 500, 1000] x {512, 1200} sweep grid. Spec §2 makes it optional ('do NOT bake the sweep into the production code path'); G.0 telemetry already pointed at 1200 x 500 as the right canonical sizing for the sticky reader topology and the small-allocation footprint of the FTS5 / vec0 hot stacks. If the orchestrator + reviewer want the sweep before deciding KEEP vs INCONCLUSIVE, it can be done as a follow-up under a debug-gated env knob without re-opening the public surface; the lookaside-call helper is already isolated in `configure_reader_lookaside`.\",\n  \"unexpected_observations\": [\n    \"AC-020 run-to-run variance widened on this G.1 sample (concurrent stddev 22.83 ms vs G.0's 11.89 ms). Run 5 in particular hit 118 ms / 4.263x — the best concurrent number observed in any G-phase run on this host so far — while run 4 hit 181 ms / 3.110x. The wider band loosens the formal KEEP threshold but suggests lookaside is doing real work when contention is the bottleneck (run 5 is plausibly an arena-pressure best-case). A larger N (e.g. N=10) would tighten the verdict; the spec calls for N=5 so I did not run more.\",\n    \"Sequential_median moved +11 ms (552 -> 563). Within noise, but consistent with the documented 'lookaside has a small overhead per allocation when the slot pool is healthy' note in the SQLite docs; sequential perf shouldn't IMPROVE from lookaside on a single-threaded fixture (no malloc-arena contention to remove), and a small regression in the 1-2% band is expected and tolerable.\",\n    \"Per-worker `LOOKASIDE_USED` hiwtr after warmup is uniform at 57 slots/worker, which is ~11% of the 500-slot capacity. AC-020's hybrid retrieval workload would push that higher (the warmup test does only a 64-call light-search loop on an empty DB). Slot_count 500 may be over-provisioned for the warmup fixture but well-sized for AC-020 + the FTS5/vec0 stacks visible in the G.0 top-call-site table. No evidence of a `LOOKASIDE_MISS_FULL` wall.\",\n    \"AC-018 drain_ms moved from 51 ms (G.0 release run) to 95 ms (G.1 release run). Still trivially under the 2 s gate, no contract impact, but worth noting if the 6.G synthesis tracks AC-018 trend. Likely host-jitter; the writer connection does NOT have lookaside applied in this packet (G.1 scope is reader-side only).\"\n  ],\n  \"alternative_hypothesis_if_revert\": \"If a follow-on run on the orchestrator side shows the concurrent_median improvement does NOT reproduce (i.e. observed median > 168 + 1 * stddev), the most likely explanation is that the dominant residual on AC-020 is NOT the glibc malloc-arena mutex but the SQLite pcache1 global mutex (G.0 reported `page_cache` = 6.29% conc with 4.01x ratio, the second-largest contention class). Lookaside reduces calls to `pcache1Alloc -> sqlite3Malloc -> __libc_malloc` but does NOT eliminate the pcache1 mutex itself, which still sits on the page-fetch hot path. Per the G.0 unexpected_observations, a per-connection (private) page cache (`PRAGMA private_cache=ON` / `SQLITE_OPEN_PRIVATECACHE`) would attack that residual; that's a candidate G.4. The G.1 numbers being just below the 1*stddev threshold are consistent with this: lookaside removed some malloc-arena calls but the pcache1-mutex floor is still there.\",\n  \"data_for_pivot\": {\n    \"if_keep\": {\n      \"next_lever\": \"G.4 — per-connection (private) page cache. G.0 telemetry called this out: page_cache (pcache1Fetch / Unpin / Alloc / Destroy) shows 4.01x growth concurrent vs sequential and is the second-largest contention path after allocator_lookaside. Lookaside masks pcache1Alloc fall-through to malloc but not the pcache1 global mutex itself. Canonical-SQLite lever: `SQLITE_OPEN_PRIVATECACHE` open flag or `PRAGMA cache=private` per-reader-connection. Distinct from the §3 do-not-retry `cache_size` global tuning entry.\",\n      \"deferred\": \"G.2 (per-worker prepared-statement cache, sticky-connection revisit of E.1) is still motivated by parse_compile = 22.52% conc, but its ratio is 0.61 (share shrinks under concurrency), so it lowers a CPU floor more than it removes a contention point. Defer until G.4 settles.\"\n    },\n    \"if_revert_or_inconclusive\": {\n      \"recommended_orchestrator_action\": \"Run an independent N=5 confirmation pass on the same commit with the same agent-verify-style guardrails. If the second pass reproduces concurrent_median ~ 161 ms (one stddev above the KEEP threshold), this is genuinely lookaside-improving-allocator-pressure but the F.0 baseline's 11.89 ms stddev was tighter than reality; KEEP on a relaxed 'concurrent_median < baseline AND speedup_median > baseline' rule is defensible (movement direction + ratio floor both pass). If the second pass shows no movement or regression, REVERT and pivot directly to G.4 (private page cache) since allocator-arena is then NOT the rate-limiting residual on this host.\",\n      \"reviewer_specific_notes_for_codex_gpt54_high\": \"Lookaside is not on the §5 do-not-retry list. No public Rust API expansion: only `#[cfg(debug_assertions)] #[doc(hidden)]` test accessors per F.0 reviewer convention, and one debug-only `ReaderRequest` variant. FFI uses `c_int` per `feedback_cross_platform_rust.md`; named symbol `ffi::SQLITE_DBCONFIG_LOOKASIDE` not magic 1001. Ordering rc captured + debug-asserted before any PRAGMA / prepare runs. AC-018 unchanged (still green, drain 95 ms). Same-snapshot cursor contract / AC-021 / AC-022 / AC-059b untouched (no read-path SQL or transaction-shape changes).\"\n    }\n  },\n  \"agent_verify_status\": \"pass\",\n  \"agent_verify_reason\": \"`./scripts/agent-verify.sh` (per F.0 reviewer block #3 — NOT `dev/agent-verify.sh`) returned rc=0 on a clean run. First fmt run flagged a rustfmt-style block-vs-inline struct expansion on the new `LookasideStatus` ReaderRequest variant; fixed by running `cargo fmt --all` and re-running. AC-017 + AC-018 release-profile runs both green prior to the AC-020 capture (AC018_NUMBERS drain_ms=95).\",\n  \"do_not_retry_cross_check\": [\n    {\"item\": \"B.1 runtime sqlite3_config(SQLITE_CONFIG_MULTITHREAD)\",                 \"did_not_re_run\": true, \"evidence\": \"G.1 only adds `sqlite3_db_config(SQLITE_DBCONFIG_LOOKASIDE)` — a per-connection allocator setting. No `sqlite3_config` (capital-C global) calls were added or modified. `git log -p f1e66bc..46e3576 -- src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs` shows no SQLITE_CONFIG_MULTITHREAD touch.\"},\n    {\"item\": \"C.1 compile-time SQLITE_THREADSAFE=2 rebuild\",                          \"did_not_re_run\": true, \"evidence\": \"No libsqlite3-sys / build.rs / Cargo.toml feature changes; canonical SQLite serialized mode unchanged. No reproducible-bin layer touched.\"},\n    {\"item\": \"E.1 read-path prepare_cached on borrow/release pool connections\",      \"did_not_re_run\": true, \"evidence\": \"No prepare_cached changes anywhere in this commit. G.2 (sticky thread-affine prepared cache) is still future-packet.\"},\n    {\"item\": \"Reader cache_size / mmap_size global tuning\",                          \"did_not_re_run\": true, \"evidence\": \"No PRAGMA cache_size / mmap_size production-default changes. Only PRAGMAs touched on reader connections at open are the pre-existing journal_mode=WAL + query_only=ON; nothing added.\"},\n    {\"item\": \"Reader open flags READ_ONLY | NO_MUTEX\",                               \"did_not_re_run\": true, \"evidence\": \"Reader open flags untouched: still `Connection::open(&path)` with default flags. Lookaside is a per-connection allocator setting, not an open-flag bit; the §3 NO_MUTEX entry is unrelated and stays not-retried.\"}\n  ],\n  \"tests_run\": [\n    \"cargo build --tests -p fathomdb-engine — green\",\n    \"cargo test -p fathomdb-engine --test reader_pool (6 tests, all green; 2 new G.1 lookaside tests + the 4 existing F.0 worker-pool tests)\",\n    \"cargo test --release -p fathomdb-engine --test perf_gates -- ac_017 ac_018 --nocapture — both green; AC018_NUMBERS drain_ms=95\",\n    \"AGENT_LONG=1 cargo test --release -p fathomdb-engine --test perf_gates ac_020_reads_do_not_serialize -- --nocapture --test-threads=1 (x5) — gate fails as expected (still chasing 5.33x), all numerics captured\",\n    \"cargo clippy --all-targets -- -D warnings — clean\",\n    \"cargo fmt --all -- --check — clean\",\n    \"./scripts/agent-verify.sh — rc=0\"\n  ],\n  \"next_phase_input\": {\n    \"for_orchestrator\": \"Codex `gpt-5.4` high reviewer mandatory on this INCONCLUSIVE per handoff §7. If the reviewer + orchestrator KEEP, pivot to G.4 (private page cache) — that lever attacks the second-largest G.0 contention class (`page_cache` 6.29% conc with 4.01x ratio) and is canonical-SQLite (`SQLITE_OPEN_PRIVATECACHE` / `PRAGMA cache=private`), distinct from the §3 do-not-retry `cache_size` global tuning entry. If the reviewer REVERTS, the same G.4 candidate becomes the next phase since the residual is then NOT allocator-arena.\",\n    \"for_packet_close\": \"G.1 is a small-radius lever; if it KEEPs the cumulative speedup vs F.0 is ~+0.19x (3.339x -> 3.530x). AC-020's 5.33x KEEP target / 5.0x packet floor is still ~1.5-1.8x away. Per handoff §9, packet success is 'every canonical-SQLite lever tried, KEEPs landed, residual gap documented for Pack 7' — not 'AC-020 closes within 0.6.0'.\"\n  }\n}\n"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":133,"cache_read_input_tokens":110213,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":133},"output_tokens":43,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"14d083b7-460f-4635-b7a8-5e1b3e7e8a72","uuid":"c44d47e6-1565-4865-bead-09caae4f7257"}
dev/plans/runs/G1-reader-lookaside-20260504T135138Z.log:8573:{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_0142Z3mmJuacKu8YTHcGaAW3","type":"tool_result","content":"File created successfully at: /home/coreyt/projects/fathomdb/dev/plan/runs/G1-reader-lookaside-output.json"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"14d083b7-460f-4635-b7a8-5e1b3e7e8a72","uuid":"137a7c3c-ba56-4cac-a4b6-78a82eb6f313","timestamp":"2026-05-04T14:10:07.379Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"create","filePath":"/home/coreyt/projects/fathomdb/dev/plan/runs/G1-reader-lookaside-output.json","content":"{\n  \"phase\": \"G.1\",\n  \"decision_self\": \"INCONCLUSIVE\",\n  \"decision_self_rationale\": \"AC-017 + AC-018 stayed green. Concurrent_median improved 168 ms -> 161 ms (-7 ms, ~4.2%) and speedup_median improved 3.339x -> 3.530x (+0.191x, no ratio worsening). Per handoff §6 / §8 the KEEP threshold is `concurrent_median < baseline - 1*stddev` = 168 - 11.89 = 156.11 ms; observed 161 ms misses the threshold by 4.89 ms (less than half a stddev). Movement is in the right direction but inside the noise band, so the implementer self-decision is INCONCLUSIVE. Lookaside-applied evidence captured below for the orchestrator + codex `gpt-5.4` high reviewer to confirm KEEP-or-REVERT.\",\n  \"commit_sha\": \"46e3576ba92047b68d1a8c8163e580e065871d8d\",\n  \"branch\": \"pack6G-G1-20260504T135138Z\",\n  \"host_caveat\": \"Same worktree host as G.0 (Linux 5.15-tegra, schedutil, ~3x slower than the Pack 5 reference machine). Cross-pack comparisons should use ratios, not absolute ms.\",\n  \"red_tests_written\": [\n    {\n      \"name\": \"reader_workers_have_lookaside_configured_with_ok_rc\",\n      \"file\": \"src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/tests/reader_pool.rs\",\n      \"red_failure_mode\": \"Compile-time: method `reader_lookaside_config_rcs_for_test` does not exist on `fathomdb_engine::Engine` (E0599). Pre-implementation. Asserts the rc of `sqlite3_db_config(LOOKASIDE)` captured at open time is SQLITE_OK (0) for every reader worker.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"name\": \"reader_workers_consume_lookaside_slots_after_warmup_read\",\n      \"file\": \"src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/tests/reader_pool.rs\",\n      \"red_failure_mode\": \"Compile-time: method `reader_lookaside_used_per_worker_for_test` does not exist on `fathomdb_engine::Engine` (E0599). Pre-implementation. Once compiling, this test would also fail at runtime if lookaside were misconfigured (e.g. ordered after a PRAGMA so SQLite silently ignored it) because `SQLITE_DBSTATUS_LOOKASIDE_USED` hiwtr would remain 0 after warmup. Initially also failed at runtime when the test read `current` instead of `hiwtr` (slots returned to the pool when the search transaction closed) — fixed by asserting on hiwtr, which is the right semantic for 'at least one slot was honored at any point'.\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"lookaside_config\": {\n    \"slot_size_bytes\": 1200,\n    \"slot_count\": 500,\n    \"applied_via\": \"raw FFI: rusqlite::ffi::sqlite3_db_config(handle, ffi::SQLITE_DBCONFIG_LOOKASIDE, NULL, 1200, 500). rusqlite 0.31's safe `set_db_config` wrapper only supports the boolean DbConfig::* variants; `SQLITE_DBCONFIG_LOOKASIDE` is explicitly commented out in `rusqlite-0.31.0/src/config.rs`. Used the named symbol `ffi::SQLITE_DBCONFIG_LOOKASIDE` (= 1001) rather than a magic number per cross-platform Rust convention.\",\n    \"ordering_assertion_rc\": \"0 (SQLITE_OK) for every reader worker, captured at open time before any PRAGMA / prepare ran on the connection. Captured per-worker into `Engine::reader_lookaside_rcs: Vec<i32>` (allow(dead_code) in release; read by `reader_lookaside_config_rcs_for_test` in debug).\"\n  },\n  \"lookaside_used_evidence\": {\n    \"method\": \"Debug-only `ReaderRequest::LookasideStatus` request broadcast to every worker (not round-robin); each worker calls `sqlite3_db_status(SQLITE_DBSTATUS_LOOKASIDE_USED)` and returns the high-water-mark out-param. `current` was tried first but decays as transactions finalize so it is unreliable for post-warmup evidence; `hiwtr` is the correct latched signal that lookaside was honored at any point.\",\n    \"after_warmup_test_workload\": \"READER_POOL_SIZE * 8 = 64 dispatched `engine.search('warmup')` calls (each routed round-robin to one of the 8 workers) on a fresh empty engine, search() returns Err but still parses + prepares + steps which exercises the lookaside arena.\",\n    \"hiwtr_per_worker\": [57, 57, 57, 57, 57, 57, 57, 57],\n    \"interpretation\": \"Every worker has hiwtr=57 slots used (well below the configured 500-slot capacity, ~11%). Uniformity across workers reflects the round-robin dispatch + the fact that `engine.search('warmup')` exercises the same transaction shape on each. AC-020's hybrid retrieval workload is more allocation-heavy and would push hiwtr higher; the test gate is 'consumed > 0', not 'saturated'.\"\n  },\n  \"ac017_runs\": [\n    {\n      \"passed\": true,\n      \"profile\": \"release\",\n      \"notes\": \"Run via `cargo test --release -p fathomdb-engine --test perf_gates -- ac_017 ac_018 --nocapture`; `test ac_017_vector_projection_freshness_p99_le_five_seconds ... ok` in 14.64 s wall.\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"ac018_runs\": [\n    {\n      \"drain_ms\": 95,\n      \"passed\": true,\n      \"notes\": \"release; AC018_NUMBERS drain_ms=95; well under the 2 s gate. Slightly higher than G.0's 51 ms (run-to-run; G.0 itself reported 56 ms in F.0 baseline).\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"ac020_runs\": [\n    {\"run\": 1, \"sequential_ms\": 582, \"concurrent_ms\": 153, \"bound_ms\": 109, \"speedup\": 3.804, \"passed_5_33x\": false, \"passed_packet_1_25_margin\": false},\n    {\"run\": 2, \"sequential_ms\": 547, \"concurrent_ms\": 161, \"bound_ms\": 102, \"speedup\": 3.398, \"passed_5_33x\": false, \"passed_packet_1_25_margin\": false},\n    {\"run\": 3, \"sequential_ms\": 593, \"concurrent_ms\": 168, \"bound_ms\": 111, \"speedup\": 3.530, \"passed_5_33x\": false, \"passed_packet_1_25_margin\": false},\n    {\"run\": 4, \"sequential_ms\": 563, \"concurrent_ms\": 181, \"bound_ms\": 105, \"speedup\": 3.110, \"passed_5_33x\": false, \"passed_packet_1_25_margin\": false},\n    {\"run\": 5, \"sequential_ms\": 503, \"concurrent_ms\": 118, \"bound_ms\": 94,  \"speedup\": 4.263, \"passed_5_33x\": false, \"passed_packet_1_25_margin\": false}\n  ],\n  \"ac020_summary\": {\n    \"sequential_ms\": {\"min\": 503, \"median\": 563, \"max\": 593, \"stddev\": 33.40},\n    \"concurrent_ms\": {\"min\": 118, \"median\": 161, \"max\": 181, \"stddev\": 22.83},\n    \"speedup\":      {\"min\": 3.110, \"median\": 3.530, \"max\": 4.263, \"stddev\": 0.428}\n  },\n  \"comparison_to_g0_baseline\": {\n    \"g0_baseline_of_record\": {\n      \"sequential_ms_median\": 552,\n      \"concurrent_ms_median\": 168,\n      \"speedup_median\": 3.339,\n      \"concurrent_ms_stddev\": 11.89,\n      \"n\": 5\n    },\n    \"g1_observed\": {\n      \"sequential_ms_median\": 563,\n      \"concurrent_ms_median\": 161,\n      \"speedup_median\": 3.530,\n      \"concurrent_ms_stddev\": 22.83,\n      \"n\": 5\n    },\n    \"deltas\": {\n      \"sequential_ms_median_delta\": \"+11 ms (+2.0%) — within run-to-run noise\",\n      \"concurrent_ms_median_delta\": \"-7 ms (-4.2%) — improvement, but inside G.0's 1*stddev band (11.89 ms)\",\n      \"speedup_median_delta\": \"+0.191x (+5.7%) — no ratio worsening\",\n      \"concurrent_ms_stddev_delta\": \"+10.94 ms — G.1 run shows higher variance, partly driven by run 5 (118 ms) and run 4 (181 ms); not a regression but a wider band that loosens the KEEP threshold further on this sample\"\n    },\n    \"keep_threshold_evaluation\": {\n      \"rule\": \"concurrent_median < g0_baseline.concurrent_median - 1 * g0_baseline.stddev\",\n      \"threshold_ms\": 156.11,\n      \"observed_ms\": 161,\n      \"verdict\": \"miss by 4.89 ms (~0.41 * stddev); does NOT meet KEEP threshold\",\n      \"ratio_floor_evaluation\": {\n        \"rule\": \"speedup_median >= g0_baseline.speedup_median\",\n        \"threshold\": 3.339,\n        \"observed\": 3.530,\n        \"verdict\": \"pass; no ratio worsening\"\n      }\n    }\n  },\n  \"optional_sweep_results\": null,\n  \"optional_sweep_notes\": \"Did not run the [128, 250, 500, 1000] x {512, 1200} sweep grid. Spec §2 makes it optional ('do NOT bake the sweep into the production code path'); G.0 telemetry already pointed at 1200 x 500 as the right canonical sizing for the sticky reader topology and the small-allocation footprint of the FTS5 / vec0 hot stacks. If the orchestrator + reviewer want the sweep before deciding KEEP vs INCONCLUSIVE, it can be done as a follow-up under a debug-gated env knob without re-opening the public surface; the lookaside-call helper is already isolated in `configure_reader_lookaside`.\",\n  \"unexpected_observations\": [\n    \"AC-020 run-to-run variance widened on this G.1 sample (concurrent stddev 22.83 ms vs G.0's 11.89 ms). Run 5 in particular hit 118 ms / 4.263x — the best concurrent number observed in any G-phase run on this host so far — while run 4 hit 181 ms / 3.110x. The wider band loosens the formal KEEP threshold but suggests lookaside is doing real work when contention is the bottleneck (run 5 is plausibly an arena-pressure best-case). A larger N (e.g. N=10) would tighten the verdict; the spec calls for N=5 so I did not run more.\",\n    \"Sequential_median moved +11 ms (552 -> 563). Within noise, but consistent with the documented 'lookaside has a small overhead per allocation when the slot pool is healthy' note in the SQLite docs; sequential perf shouldn't IMPROVE from lookaside on a single-threaded fixture (no malloc-arena contention to remove), and a small regression in the 1-2% band is expected and tolerable.\",\n    \"Per-worker `LOOKASIDE_USED` hiwtr after warmup is uniform at 57 slots/worker, which is ~11% of the 500-slot capacity. AC-020's hybrid retrieval workload would push that higher (the warmup test does only a 64-call light-search loop on an empty DB). Slot_count 500 may be over-provisioned for the warmup fixture but well-sized for AC-020 + the FTS5/vec0 stacks visible in the G.0 top-call-site table. No evidence of a `LOOKASIDE_MISS_FULL` wall.\",\n    \"AC-018 drain_ms moved from 51 ms (G.0 release run) to 95 ms (G.1 release run). Still trivially under the 2 s gate, no contract impact, but worth noting if the 6.G synthesis tracks AC-018 trend. Likely host-jitter; the writer connection does NOT have lookaside applied in this packet (G.1 scope is reader-side only).\"\n  ],\n  \"alternative_hypothesis_if_revert\": \"If a follow-on run on the orchestrator side shows the concurrent_median improvement does NOT reproduce (i.e. observed median > 168 + 1 * stddev), the most likely explanation is that the dominant residual on AC-020 is NOT the glibc malloc-arena mutex but the SQLite pcache1 global mutex (G.0 reported `page_cache` = 6.29% conc with 4.01x ratio, the second-largest contention class). Lookaside reduces calls to `pcache1Alloc -> sqlite3Malloc -> __libc_malloc` but does NOT eliminate the pcache1 mutex itself, which still sits on the page-fetch hot path. Per the G.0 unexpected_observations, a per-connection (private) page cache (`PRAGMA private_cache=ON` / `SQLITE_OPEN_PRIVATECACHE`) would attack that residual; that's a candidate G.4. The G.1 numbers being just below the 1*stddev threshold are consistent with this: lookaside removed some malloc-arena calls but the pcache1-mutex floor is still there.\",\n  \"data_for_pivot\": {\n    \"if_keep\": {\n      \"next_lever\": \"G.4 — per-connection (private) page cache. G.0 telemetry called this out: page_cache (pcache1Fetch / Unpin / Alloc / Destroy) shows 4.01x growth concurrent vs sequential and is the second-largest contention path after allocator_lookaside. Lookaside masks pcache1Alloc fall-through to malloc but not the pcache1 global mutex itself. Canonical-SQLite lever: `SQLITE_OPEN_PRIVATECACHE` open flag or `PRAGMA cache=private` per-reader-connection. Distinct from the §3 do-not-retry `cache_size` global tuning entry.\",\n      \"deferred\": \"G.2 (per-worker prepared-statement cache, sticky-connection revisit of E.1) is still motivated by parse_compile = 22.52% conc, but its ratio is 0.61 (share shrinks under concurrency), so it lowers a CPU floor more than it removes a contention point. Defer until G.4 settles.\"\n    },\n    \"if_revert_or_inconclusive\": {\n      \"recommended_orchestrator_action\": \"Run an independent N=5 confirmation pass on the same commit with the same agent-verify-style guardrails. If the second pass reproduces concurrent_median ~ 161 ms (one stddev above the KEEP threshold), this is genuinely lookaside-improving-allocator-pressure but the F.0 baseline's 11.89 ms stddev was tighter than reality; KEEP on a relaxed 'concurrent_median < baseline AND speedup_median > baseline' rule is defensible (movement direction + ratio floor both pass). If the second pass shows no movement or regression, REVERT and pivot directly to G.4 (private page cache) since allocator-arena is then NOT the rate-limiting residual on this host.\",\n      \"reviewer_specific_notes_for_codex_gpt54_high\": \"Lookaside is not on the §5 do-not-retry list. No public Rust API expansion: only `#[cfg(debug_assertions)] #[doc(hidden)]` test accessors per F.0 reviewer convention, and one debug-only `ReaderRequest` variant. FFI uses `c_int` per `feedback_cross_platform_rust.md`; named symbol `ffi::SQLITE_DBCONFIG_LOOKASIDE` not magic 1001. Ordering rc captured + debug-asserted before any PRAGMA / prepare runs. AC-018 unchanged (still green, drain 95 ms). Same-snapshot cursor contract / AC-021 / AC-022 / AC-059b untouched (no read-path SQL or transaction-shape changes).\"\n    }\n  },\n  \"agent_verify_status\": \"pass\",\n  \"agent_verify_reason\": \"`./scripts/agent-verify.sh` (per F.0 reviewer block #3 — NOT `dev/agent-verify.sh`) returned rc=0 on a clean run. First fmt run flagged a rustfmt-style block-vs-inline struct expansion on the new `LookasideStatus` ReaderRequest variant; fixed by running `cargo fmt --all` and re-running. AC-017 + AC-018 release-profile runs both green prior to the AC-020 capture (AC018_NUMBERS drain_ms=95).\",\n  \"do_not_retry_cross_check\": [\n    {\"item\": \"B.1 runtime sqlite3_config(SQLITE_CONFIG_MULTITHREAD)\",                 \"did_not_re_run\": true, \"evidence\": \"G.1 only adds `sqlite3_db_config(SQLITE_DBCONFIG_LOOKASIDE)` — a per-connection allocator setting. No `sqlite3_config` (capital-C global) calls were added or modified. `git log -p f1e66bc..46e3576 -- src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs` shows no SQLITE_CONFIG_MULTITHREAD touch.\"},\n    {\"item\": \"C.1 compile-time SQLITE_THREADSAFE=2 rebuild\",                          \"did_not_re_run\": true, \"evidence\": \"No libsqlite3-sys / build.rs / Cargo.toml feature changes; canonical SQLite serialized mode unchanged. No reproducible-bin layer touched.\"},\n    {\"item\": \"E.1 read-path prepare_cached on borrow/release pool connections\",      \"did_not_re_run\": true, \"evidence\": \"No prepare_cached changes anywhere in this commit. G.2 (sticky thread-affine prepared cache) is still future-packet.\"},\n    {\"item\": \"Reader cache_size / mmap_size global tuning\",                          \"did_not_re_run\": true, \"evidence\": \"No PRAGMA cache_size / mmap_size production-default changes. Only PRAGMAs touched on reader connections at open are the pre-existing journal_mode=WAL + query_only=ON; nothing added.\"},\n    {\"item\": \"Reader open flags READ_ONLY | NO_MUTEX\",                               \"did_not_re_run\": true, \"evidence\": \"Reader open flags untouched: still `Connection::open(&path)` with default flags. Lookaside is a per-connection allocator setting, not an open-flag bit; the §3 NO_MUTEX entry is unrelated and stays not-retried.\"}\n  ],\n  \"tests_run\": [\n    \"cargo build --tests -p fathomdb-engine — green\",\n    \"cargo test -p fathomdb-engine -